<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S.-Korea Missile Talks Set  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- U.S. and North Korean officials will hold
missile talks in July, the State Department said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The discussions, which will take place on July 10-12 in Kuala
Lumpur, Malaysia, will cover a wide range of topics, including U.S.
concerns about North Korea's missile activities and exports plans.
Robert Einhorn, who covers nonproliferation issues at the
department, will talk with North Korea's U.S. affairs officials.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, North Korea pledged to refrain from long-range
missile tests after the United States lifted some economic
sanctions against it. Washington said it would open trade with
North Korea in nonmilitary goods, open air travel and shipping
routes, and ease restrictions on U.S. investment in the communist
nation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
