<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 02:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gay Eagle Scout Loses Court Fight  </HEADLINE>
By JEFFREY GOLD
<TEXT>
<P>
   MATAWAN, N.J. (AP) -- Boy Scout Troop 73, ground zero for a
dispute over gay scout leaders, can no longer be found here. It
folded several years ago, crippled by dwindling ranks and a
shortage of adult leaders.
</P>
<P>
   For a time, one of its adult leaders was James Dale, an Eagle
Scout who became assistant scoutmaster after turning 18. In 1990,
the Boy Scouts of America ousted Dale after learning he is gay.
</P>
<P>
   Dale's 10-year challenge to that decision ended Wednesday when
the U.S. Supreme Court voted 5-4 that the Scouts can bar
homosexuals from serving as troop leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're delighted that the ruling was in our favor,'' said James
W. Kay, executive of the Scouts' Monmouth Council, which revoked
Dale's registration as an adult leader. ''We're equally delighted,
if not more so, that hopefully this now gets put behind us.''
</P>
<P>
   Reaction on Main Street's compact business district echoed Kay's
feelings.
</P>
<P>
   William H. Seber, owner of OK Sales and Rod Shop, a haven for
restoring classic cars, said he disliked the thought of homosexuals
working with boys.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're doing what I consider unnatural acts,'' said Seber,
52. ''Why give them the opportunity to be around kids who don't
really know better?''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Johannesen, 15, a former Cub Scout, approved of the
decision, but added that a gay leader would not make him
uncomfortable.
</P>
<P>
   However, the ruling would make gay scouts hide their
orientation, said Johannesen, who was working behind the counter at
the Sportscard Zone, a mile from the Matawan United Methodist
Church which sponsored Troop 73 when Dale was its assistant
scoutmaster.
</P>
<P>
   Dale said it was a sad day for him, but a worse day for the Boy
Scouts. By acknowledging publicly that it has an anti-gay policy,
the Boy Scouts risk losing youth and adult members who do not want
to be part of an exclusionary organization, Dale said.
</P>
<P>
   Part of Dale's argument stemmed from his experience in New
Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   His first troop, which met at the King of Kings Lutheran Church
in Middletown, was forced to disband when an adult leader became
ill. He said two other troops also folded due to a lack of adult
supervision.
</P>
<P>
   Dale, who became an Eagle Scout at 17, was determined to become
an adult leader. In 1988, shortly after turning 18, he signed up to
be an adult member and agreed to become an assistant scoutmaster
for Troop 73.
</P>
<P>
   Dale was 19 in 1990 when he was identified in a newspaper
article as co-president of a campus lesbian and gay student group
at Rutgers University. The Monmouth Council then revoked his
registration as an adult leader.
</P>
<P>
   The Boys Scouts consider homosexuality contrary to their oath
requiring scouts to be ''morally straight.''
</P>
<P>
   Dale sued the scouts in 1992, just after New Jersey's
anti-discrimination law was expanded to protect the civil rights of
gay people.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the Boy Scouts are clearly an anti-gay group, New
Jersey schools must consider severing their relationships with
scouting chapters, said Ruth Harlow of the Lambda Legal Defense and
Education Fund, one of Dale's lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   ''There will be fallout in New Jersey,'' she said. ''Public
institutions (and) public schools cannot associate with a
discriminatory program.''
</P>
<P>
   Colorado-based Focus on the Family cheered the court for dealing
''a severe blow to the gay rights agenda. Gay activists failed in
their attempt to destroy a nearly century-old American
institution.''
</P>
<P>
   But Scott Cozza, an adult Scout leader in California and
president of Scouting For All, which advocates letting homosexuals
join, said: ''The Boy Scouts, in a weird sort of way, have been
outed. They are out of the closet. They are a bigoted organization.
I know a lot of my friends are not going to keep their kids in
scouting.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Boy Scouts of America: http://www.bsa.scouting.org
</P>
<P>
   Lambda Legal Defense and Education Fund:
http://www.lambdalegal.org
</P>
<P>
   Focus on the Family: http://www.family.org
</P>
<P>
   Scouting For All: http://www.scoutingforall.org/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
