<HEADLINE> Dow Falls 110; Nasdaq Drops 38  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks fell sharply Thursday as investors'
enthusiasm disappeared following the Federal Reserve's announcement
on interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   In the first hour of trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones
industrial average was down 110.00 at 10,417.83.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators also dropped. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index was down 7.41 at 1,447.41, and the Nasdaq composite index was
down 38.43 at 3,901.91.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the Fed left interest rates unchanged, but noted
that inflation risks remain in the economy. The warning on
inflation led many analysts to expect that the Fed will raise rates
at its August meeting.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, analysts said, the market may find excuses to
remain stalled in a narrow range. Stocks had advanced modestly in
the days leading up to the meeting, leading investors to take some
profits Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Financial stocks, which are highly sensitive to rising interest
rates, pulled the Dow lower. J.P. Morgan fell $2.125 to $114.50 and
American Express fell $1 to $52.188.
</P>
<P>
   On the New York Stock Exchange, Eli Lilly soared $18.438 to
$105.563 after announcing that an independent board gave a
favorable review to its drug Zovant, used to treat sepsis. The
experimental drug, if approved, would be the first drug approved
for the treatment of sepsis, a disease in which the body's systems
fail due to infection.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 4-to-3 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 128.94 million
shares, slightly ahead of Wednesday's pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 3.61 to 517.38.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 0.6 percent. In
afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was down 2.1 percent,
Britain's FT-SE 100 was down 1.0 percent, and France's CAC-40 was
down 1.7 percent.
</P>
