<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 11:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reno Mulls New Laws After Elian  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL J. SNIFFEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Attorney General Janet Reno and immigration
officials will review whether the case of Elian Gonzalez
demonstrates a need for new procedures or regulations, such as a
minimum age for children seeking asylum on their own.
</P>
<P>
   ''One of the questions I want to ask is, what if anything,
should be done,'' Reno said at her weekly news conference Thursday.
''We will be looking at it to see if there is any lesson learned,
anything that should be done.''
</P>
<P>
   The government's own legal briefs conceded that Immigration and
Naturalization Service regulations were silent on how old a child
must be in order to apply for asylum without consent from parents.
</P>
<P>
   The INS concluded that Elian's father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez,
should speak for the 6-year-old in immigration matters, and Juan
Miguel wanted to return the boy to his home in Cuba. Elian's Miami
relatives tried unsuccessfully to get U.S. courts to force the
government to accept what the relatives said was Elian's own
application for asylum.
</P>
<P>
   ''Where do you draw the line between a 6-year-old and a
12-year-old? How do you make these judgments?'' Reno asked. She was
referring to an appellate court ruling in the 1970s case of Walter
Polovchak, who sought asylum rather than return to the Soviet
Union, that age 12 was the lower limit of when a child should be
allowed to speak separately from parents on such issues.
</P>
<P>
   But Reno stopped short of advocating a regulation fixing a
specific age.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it's going to depend on the child,'' she said. ''All I
want to do is ... see if there is anything that we can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Overall, she said, the case is ''a mixture of so many different
things: A little boy who lost his mother, a country that is not
free. It is one of the few countries that is not a democratic
nation in this hemisphere. It's a story of families that have
disagreements. It is a story of so much of human life.
</P>
<P>
   ''And yet, in the end, he is with his father, and I am glad of
that. I just wish he were with his father in a democratic, free
country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
