<HEADLINE> Clinton Names New No. 2 at CIA  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton has selected a career
intelligence officer to serve in the No. 2 spot in the Central
Intelligence Agency, CIA Director George Tenet announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton designated John E. McLaughlin as acting deputy director
of central intelligence. He succeeds Air Force Gen. John Gordon,
who was sworn in on Wednesday as director of the new National
Nuclear Security Administration in the Department of Energy.
</P>
<P>
   McLaughlin, 58, has served as CIA's deputy director for
intelligence, the CIA's analysis division, since July 1997. Before
that, he served as vice chairman for estimates at the CIA and as
acting chairman of the National Intelligence Council.
</P>
<P>
   An administration official, speaking on the condition of
anonymity, said that Clinton was expected to formally nominate
McLaughlin to the post soon but that the paperwork was not yet
ready.
</P>
<P>
   McLaughlin was put in on an acting basis, in the meantime,
because it was important to fill the CIA vacancy, the official
said.
</P>
<P>
   Once formally nominated, McLaughlin's post is subject to Senate
confirmation.
</P>
<P>
   McLaughlin has worked at the CIA since 1972.
</P>
<P>
   ''His knowledge of both world affairs and the American foreign
policy process is deep and wide,'' Tenet said in a statement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
