<DOCNO> APW20000629.0032 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 14:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HUD Gun Safety Coalition Grows  </HEADLINE>
By PAUL SHEPARD
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- HUD Secretary Andrew Cuomo said Thursday that
support continues to grow for a gun safety coalition even though
the House of Representatives recently voted to block federal
funding of the program.
</P>
<P>
   Joined by Reps. Carolyn McCarthy, D-N.Y., Patrick Kennedy,
D-R.I., and more than a dozen police officials from around the
country, Cuomo said at a press conference that more than 500
communities have signed up for the Communities for Safer Guns
Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   ''The continued growth of the coalition and now the added
support from the law enforcement community shows there is a
widespread belief in what it was created to do,'' Cuomo said.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition formed in March around a pledge signed by Smith &AMP;
Wesson, the nation's largest gun maker, and federal officials
seeking to make guns safer. As part of the pact, cities would give
Smith &AMP; Wesson a preference when buying guns for law enforcement
officials.
</P>
<P>
   The preference provision of the agreement is the subject of a
federal lawsuit filed by seven gun makers and a gun industry trade
group.
</P>
<P>
   Federal lawmakers have sent mixed messages on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, the House voted, 218-207, to prevent HUD from
working with the Communities for Safer Guns Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   But on Monday, the House narrowly beat back an effort to scuttle
the government's pact with Smith &AMP; Wesson for the use of safety
devices.
</P>
<P>
   The Monday vote, on an amendment to a spending bill sponsored by
Rep. John Hostettler, R-Ind., was a setback to rival gun makers and
the National Rifle Association, which have criticized the pact.
</P>
<P>
   Hostettler has called the Smith &AMP; Wesson agreement ''backdoor
gun control through coercion and through threat of litigation.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I am outraged by the attempt of the congressional Republicans
to tie the hands of these local law enforcement officials as well
as federal agencies in their efforts to reduce gun violence,''
Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   HUD: http://www.hud.gov/news.html
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
