<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 14:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bill Seeks Slave Labor Recognition  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Two black members of Congress introduced a
bill Thursday that recognizes contributions by slaves in the
construction of the U.S. Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   Reps. J.C. Watts, R-Okla., and John Lewis, D-Ga., are seeking to
create a task force to study the history and contributions of slave
laborers in the construction of the building.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's time the role African-Americans played be fully realized
and they be given the honorable recognition that they deserve,''
Watts said.
</P>
<P>
   A report last March by Washington's WRC-TV estimated that 400 of
the 650 laborers working on the Capitol building in the 1790s were
enslaved blacks.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Senate historian's office said little research has
been done on this issue. ''Our knowledge of the laborers, black or
white, is not very good,'' said Betty Koed, the Senate's assistant
historian.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
