<DOCNO> APW20000629.0034 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 14:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Falls 62; Nasdaq Off 40  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks fell Thursday as investors' enthusiasm
disappeared following the Federal Reserve's announcement on
interest rates. But some consumer issues posted gains as investors
looked for stocks that will perform well even if the economy slows.
</P>
<P>
   In afternoon trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average was down 61.61 at 10,466.63.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators also dropped. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index was down 7.15 at 1,447.67, and the Nasdaq composite index was
down 39.65 at 3,900.69.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the Fed left interest rates unchanged, but noted
that inflation risks remain in the economy. The warning on
inflation led many analysts to expect that the Fed will raise rates
at its August meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think the game is over. This is more like the seventh
inning stretch,'' said John Forelli, senior vice president at
Independence Investment Associates in Boston. ''The Fed is waiting
to see whether economic activity slows substantially. I don't think
any investors can rule out action in August.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, analysts said, the market may find excuses to
remain stalled in a narrow range. Stocks had advanced modestly in
the days leading up to the meeting, leading investors to take some
profits Thursday. Also, traders said investors were unloading some
stocks ahead of the Independence Day weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Financial stocks, which are highly sensitive to rising interest
rates, pulled the Dow lower. J.P. Morgan fell $2.625 to $114 and
Citigroup fell 56.25 cents to $63.563.
</P>
<P>
   But investors were also taking profits from the technology
stocks that have risen in recent sessions. LSI Logic fell $5.313 to
$53.813 and Cisco fell $1.875 to $61.688.
</P>
<P>
   On the New York Stock Exchange, Eli Lilly soared $15.75 to
$102.875 after announcing that an independent board gave a
favorable review to its drug Zovant, used to treat sepsis. The
experimental drug, which still needs approval from the Food and
Drug Administration, would be the first drug approved for the
treatment of sepsis, a disease in which the body's systems fail due
to infection.
</P>
<P>
   Unisys plunged $8.25 to $15.375 after warning that its
second-quarter revenue and earnings would be disappointing.
Investors are punishing companies that demonstrate any evidence of
earnings weakness.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer goods stocks made the most convincing gains, rising on
the hope that whether the economy grows or falters, products like
toothpaste and soap will continue to drive sales. Kimberly Clark
rose $2.063 to $56.125 and Johnson &AMP; Johnson rose 87.5 cents to
$98.875.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 10-to-9 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 686.81 million
shares, slightly ahead of Wednesday's pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 5.22 to 515.77.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
