<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Big Mac Attack Leader Goes on Trial  </HEADLINE>
By MORT ROSENBLUM
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- In a nation that loves its dinner, the mustachioed
folk hero who led a Big Mac Attack is leapfrogging his vandalism
trial into a planetary protest against what he calls malbouffe:
lousy food.
</P>
<P>
   ''Eating is not a neutral act,'' Jose Bove tells reporters,
explaining how what began as a riposte to a punitive U.S. duty on
French cheese bloomed into a popular uprising against big
agriculture and globalization in general.
</P>
<P>
   At least 30,000 people are expected Friday in Millau, in the
heart of Roquefort country, where Bove and nine others were
arrested last August after trashing a soon-to-open McDonald's.
</P>
<P>
   The food fight began when France refused to import hormone-laced
U.S. beef unless it was labeled. Washington added a 100 percent tax
to Roquefort, foie gras and other French delicacies. Bove's farm
lobby group struck back.
</P>
<P>
   A Millau court will hear arguments Friday and Saturday and
deliver a judgment later this summer. But the Confederation
Paysanne, the farmers' group Bove heads, seized the moment to
display support.
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen open-air forums led by activists from around the world
plan to skewer multinationals and industrial cuisine. A free rock
concert will entertain sympathizers arriving by bus from across
France.
</P>
<P>
   American speakers include Lori Wallach, president of Global
Trade Watch, and Bill Christison, who heads the Washington-based
National Family Farm Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   ''They'll learn to think twice before locking us up,'' Bove
said. And, he added, French leaders who assume the rotating
European Union presidency on Saturday will see they must resist
genetically altered food imports.
</P>
<P>
   Bove spent three weeks in jail last year until he decided to
post bail. He held aloft his manacled wrists for a photo that
crystalized his fame.
</P>
<P>
   Although he chose ''McDo'' only as a symbol of a larger foe,
others attacked the franchise chain across France. In April,
Brittany separatists blew up a McDonald's, killing the young French
woman who managed it.
</P>
<P>
   Bove has served an unrelated eight-month suspended sentence for
plowing up a field planted in transgenic corn. The McDonald's
charge carries a maximum penalty of five years imprisonment and a
hefty fine.
</P>
<P>
   A parade of defense witnesses is to include South American
farmers and anti-globalization economists. Bove promised to walk
out of the trial if any were excluded.
</P>
<P>
   Bove's book, ''The World Is Not Merchandise,'' has sold 80,000
copies, and he jets from Seattle to the South Pacific to espouse
his cause. Business Week named him among 50 movers who are shaping
a new Europe.
</P>
<P>
   President Jacques Chirac has gone from avoiding him to embracing
him and Prime Minister Lionel Jospin takes him to lunch.
</P>
<P>
   Bove's alfalfa-roots movement has galvanized the fractured left
wing of French politics, while winning wide support from
conservative leaders who recognize a phenomenon when they say it.
</P>
<P>
   Though Bove bills himself as a sheep farmer who produces milk
for Roquefort, his early years were spent in Berkeley where his
parents studied biochemistry.
</P>
<P>
   As a young intellectual, he traveled with Greenpeace to protest
French nuclear tests in Tahitian waters. As a farmers' advocate, he
translates complex socio-economic theory into barnyard language.
</P>
<P>
   Asked once in an interview why he didn't resolve his differences
by having McDonald's put Roquefort on cheeseburgers, he replied,
''That would be like selling holy water in a sex shop.''
</P>
<P>
   Bove's specific appeal in France is his remarkable symbolic
similarity to Asterix, a cartoon figure who gulps magic potion like
Popeye eats spinach to knock Romans out of their sandals with a
vicious left uppercut.
</P>
<P>
   Both are compact, with an outsized mustache, a wry grin and a
mission to save workaday Frenchmen from an evil empire.
</P>
<P>
   Bove's main targets are the World Trade Organization,
multinationals and governments that push scientifically engineered
food. This, he said, crushes the small-time producers who insist on
quality and taste.
</P>
<P>
   His complaints are vague about McDonald's, which counters that
well over 90 percent of its meals sold in France come from French
farms. Eighty new outlets are to open this year, joining the 800 in
every corner of the country.
</P>
<P>
   The Millau McDo is closing Friday and Saturday for reasons its
manager considers obvious. But McDonald's workers who sympathize
with Bove's cause say the farmers promised to protect the place.
</P>
<P>
   In its pretrial coverage, the Paris daily ''Liberation'' sampled
customers who liked both Bove and Ronald McDonald without being
troubled by the paradox.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper concluded: ''So it looks like you can be crazy
about Bove while throwing yourself at a 'Best of Big Mac' menu and
chocolate brownies.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-29-00 1431 </TRAILER>
