<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wisconsin Legislators Sue EPA  </HEADLINE>
By REBECCA SINDERBRAND
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Wisconsin legislators sued the Environmental
Protection Agency on Thursday over clean air regulations they blame
for high gas prices in southern Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, filed in U.S. District court here, claims EPA
failed to consider the price consequences of new formulation
requirements for cleaner-burning gasoline. It seeks suspension of
the rules, which went into effect June 1.
</P>
<P>
   The lawmakers said the air quality problems that had been the
basis for imposing the regulations had significantly improved,
making costly reformulated gas unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
   ''These regulations have had a devastating impact on the price
of gas,'' said State Rep. Mark Green, a Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Wisconsin Assembly Speaker Scott Jensen said the reformulated
gas that EPA required was costing consumers in some areas of the
state anywhere from 25 to 50 cents more per gallon. EPA officials
had calculated the cost going to the ethanol-blended gas at just
1.2 cents a gallon.
</P>
<P>
   Wisconsin Gov. Tommy Thompson told the House Judiciary Committee
on Wednesday that he blamed the Clinton administration's
''overbearing environmental policies'' for gasoline price surges in
the Milwaukee and Chicago areas.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a problem borne of the federal government ... and a
problem that must be solved by the federal government,'' the
Republican governor said. ''The administration has refused to give
us any relief.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Thompson and Illinois Gov. George Ryan, also a Republican,
have asked EPA for waivers from regulations aimed at reducing
pollution in high smog urban areas.
</P>
<P>
   The Wisconsin lawmakers, all Republicans, complained that
temporary waivers had been granted to St. Louis, home of House
Democratic Leader Dick Gephardt, while southern Wisconsin had not
had its needs addressed.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are basically at our wits' end trying to get relief from
the EPA,'' said State Rep. Paul Ryan. ''We need solutions, not
finger-pointing.''
</P>
<P>
   EPA spokesman Dave Cohen said the agency was ''very concerned''
about prices in Milwaukee and Chicago, but was hesitant to grant a
waiver.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are keeping all options open, because we will do whatever
is necessary to bring prices down,'' said Cohen, ''but we know from
our initial investigation that the problem does not stem from
reformulated gasoline.''
</P>
<P>
   Prices in the Milwaukee area reached more that $2 but have
fallen in recent days. The average price Wednesday for unleaded
regular was $1.86 a gallon, according to AAA Wisconsin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-29-00 1507 </TRAILER>
