<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 15:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Male Athletes Lose Court Appeal  </HEADLINE>
By RICHARD CARELLI
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A Supreme Court appeal by male athletes
challenging Illinois State University's elimination of its men's
wrestling and soccer teams to help equalize opportunities for both
genders failed Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Without comment, the justices left intact rulings that threw out
the lawsuit against ISU and its officials.
</P>
<P>
   A federal law, known as Title IX of the Education Amendments of
1972, bans gender discrimination by any program receiving federal
money. Virtually all of the nation's universities and colleges
receive some federal aid, and the law has been used to force
schools to equalize the money spent for men's and women's
athletics.
</P>
<P>
   ISU attorney Carol Posegate said the ruling upholds the
decision-making authority of individual institutions. ''The courts
have been reluctant to stand in the shoes of the various colleges
and universities and make decisions about how the money is to be
spent,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Posegate said the decision does not embrace any particular
method for establishing Title IX equality.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think the law was ever intended to dictate the
specifics of how it is achieved,'' she said. ''There are going to
be great differences from one campus to another.''
</P>
<P>
   Chicago attorney Lou Goldstein, who represents the male athletes
who sued, did not immediately return telephone messages seeking
comment Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the male athletes argued that eliminating the men's
teams in 1995 made them victims of illegal and unconstitutional
gender bias. Similar lawsuits have been filed by male students at
other schools throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
   Lower courts disagreed, saying Illinois State's elimination of
the two men's teams, along with the addition of a women's soccer
team, was a legal way to comply with the equality in athletics that
federal law and regulations require.
</P>
<P>
   Federal regulations say schools generally comply with Title IX
when they show that the number of women participating in athletics
is ''substantially proportionate'' to their enrollment.
</P>
<P>
   In upholding the university's decision last December, the 7th
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals said, ''A holding that universities
cannot achieve substantial proportionality by cutting men's
programs is tantamount to a requirement that universities ... add
women's sports programs.
</P>
<P>
   ''This result would ignore the financial and budgetary
constraints that universities face,'' the appeals court said.
</P>
<P>
   The appeal acted on Thursday drew the support of a prominent
former wrestling coach, House Speaker Dennis Hastert. The Illinois
Republican joined in a friend-of-the-court brief urging the
justices to rule that some remedy should be available when ''men's
teams are ... cut for no reason other than to meet the
proportionality quota -- and not to increase opportunities for
women.''
</P>
<P>
   The case is Boulahanis v. Board of Regents, 99-1561.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Appeals court ruling:
http://www.uscourts.gov/links.html and click on 7th Circuit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-29-00 1510 </TRAILER>
