<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 15:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> College Pupils Warned on Meningitis  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID PITT
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- College freshmen living in dorms should be told
about the risks of contracting meningitis, and a vaccine should be
made available to those who want it, the government said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The recommendation was issued by the Centers for Disease Control
and Prevention.
</P>
<P>
   The rate of meningitis among college students living in
dormitories is about 4.6 per 100,000, higher than that of any age
group other than children under 2. Still, the rate for college
students falls under the threshold for a mandatory vaccination
campaign of 10 per 100,000.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are pleased the CDC has finally published its
recommendation regarding college students and the increasing threat
of meningococcal disease on campus,'' said David Spilker, president
of the Meningitis Foundation of America.
</P>
<P>
   Meningitis strikes as many as 3,000 Americans each year and is
responsible for about 300 deaths annually. Symptoms include
headache, fever and a stiff neck.
</P>
<P>
   Among college students, there are 100 to 125 cases of meningitis
annually, resulting in five to 15 deaths. Another five to 15
students suffer serious damage such as deafness, brain damage or
loss of limbs.
</P>
<P>
   The government also said freshmen who were vaccinated three to
five years before entering college should consider revaccination
because antibody levels decline rapidly over two to three years.
</P>
<P>
   Lynn Bozof of Atlanta was relieved to hear the government
recommendations. Her son, Evan, was a junior at Georgia
Southwestern in Americus in 1998 when he died of bacterial
meningitis, 26 days after calling home with a bad headache.
</P>
<P>
   ''I didn't know anything about meningitis. I didn't know a
vaccine existed,'' Bozof said. ''To find out it had been around for
30 years, can you imagine how I felt?''
</P>
<P>
   She added: ''I'm really glad that the information will be
getting out to students and parents so they can now make informed
decisions about their health and take charge of it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
