<HEADLINE> Oil Spill Endangers African Penguins  </HEADLINE>
By MIKE COHEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) -- At least two fifths of the
world's African penguin population are endangered by an oil spill
in an environmental disaster that keeps growing, conservation
officials said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The spill has struck the waters off Cape Town, especially Dassen
Island, which holds the world's largest colony of African penguins,
and Robben Island, home to the third largest.
</P>
<P>
   Rescuers were working to round up as many as possible of the
55,000 penguins on Dassen and the 19,000 on Robben.
</P>
<P>
   ''This evacuation is the biggest-ever effort to save sea birds
worldwide,'' said Horst Kleinschmidt, a senior official in South
Africa's environmental department.
</P>
<P>
   The oil has soiled or is threatening to soil more than 40
percent of the estimated 150,000-180,000 African penguins in the
world, said conservationist Estelle van der Merwe.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental officials have asked the South African defense
force to send vehicles, planes and ships to help volunteers and
international experts working to capture birds on the two islands.
The military is considering the request.
</P>
<P>
   The disaster began when a Panamanian tanker, the Treasure, sank
six miles off Cape Town on June 23 and two of its fuel tanks
ruptured. The slick quickly hit Robben Island and on Wednesday
reached Dassen.
</P>
<P>
   ''At least 20,000 penguins have been oiled,'' said van der
Merwe, of the Southern African National Foundation for the
Conservation of Coastal Birds. ''It's really devastating what's
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 10,000 soiled birds have been brought to the
foundation's rehabilitation centers so far. About 50 have died, van
der Merwe said, adding she expected many more deaths. It takes two
people up to an hour to clean each bird.
</P>
<P>
   The spill came in the middle of the penguins' breeding season,
and thousands of chicks and eggs are expected to be lost.
</P>
<P>
   Plastic sheeting fencing has been placed on Dassen Island to
prevent penguins from reaching the polluted water, said David
Daitz, chief executive of the Western Cape Nature Conservation
Board.
</P>
<P>
   After they are evacuated, the birds will be taken about 560
miles east to the town of Port Elizabeth on the mainland, where
they are to be released into the sea.
</P>
<P>
   The birds are expected to swim home in about 11 days, which
authorities hope will give them time to clean up the spill.
Officials hope 95 percent of the penguins will survive the
relocation.
</P>
<P>
   A few hundred Robben Island penguins were evacuated to Port
Elizabeth earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   Officials were still assessing how the spill would affect bird
populations north of Dassen, Kleinschmidt said. The island is
located about five miles off South Africa's west coast, and about
37 miles north of Cape Town. Robben is about four miles north of
Cape Town.
</P>
<P>
   The Treasure went down carrying 1,300 tons of heavy bunker oil.
About 900 tons are estimated to remain in its tanks. An operation
to pump it into other vessels was due to begin Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Before sinking, the Treasure developed a 17-by-10 yard hole in
the hull -- apparently either from rust or a crack related to its
age.
</P>
<P>
   The African penguin, also known as the jackass or Blackfooted
penguin, can be found along the coast of South Africa, and is the
only penguin species to live on the continent. On average, African
penguins are more than 18 inches high and weigh about 7.5 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Other penguin species, with populations numbering in the
millions, live in Antarctica and the southern tip of South America.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
