<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 15:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Releases N. Korea Energy Aid  </HEADLINE>
By TOM RAUM
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton released a $20 million
installment in energy aid to North Korea on Thursday, saying the
communist regime appeared to be living up to a commitment to freeze
its nuclear weapons program.
</P>
<P>
   The funds go to the Korean Peninsula Energy Development
Organization to buy fuel oil to help generate electricity while an
international consortium completes work on two new nuclear reactors
in North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   The payments are made under a 1994 agreement and can only be
freed if Clinton certifies that North Korea is complying with its
obligations under the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea asserts that it has neither the intention nor the
capacity to develop nuclear weapons amid its economic difficulties.
But last November, a congressional report suggested there was
''significant evidence that undeclared nuclear weapons development
activities continues'' in North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   However, in his certification, Clinton asserted that, ''the
United States has made and is continuing to make significant
progress on eliminating the North Korean ballistic missile threat,
including further missile tests and its ballistic missile
exports.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton at a news conference on Wednesday praised North Korea's
recent efforts to ease frictions with South Korea, but added,
''They still have a missile program. And so it's still something
that the United States has to be mindful of and to prepare and to
deal with and ... to keep up with.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the 1994 agreement, North Korea promised to freeze its
suspected nuclear weapons program.
</P>
<P>
   The pact calls for a U.S.-led international consortium to build
two nuclear reactors in North Korea and provide fuel oil until the
first reactor is completed.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, Japan, South Korea and the European Union are
providing funds for the $4.6 billion project by the Korean
Peninsula Energy Development Organization.
</P>
<P>
   The organization had planned to build the first of the reactors
by 2003. But officials recently said the completion might be
delayed by ''several years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
