<HEADLINE> Private Firms To Expand Army Housing  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Army on Thursday announced that it
selected Fort Hood Military Housing, LP, a joint venture between
companies in California and Georgia, to renovate and expand
military family housing at Fort Hood, Texas. It said the work could
be worth $4 billion to the companies over the coming 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   The participating companies, Lend Lease Actus of Napa, Calif.,
and Trammell Crow Residential of Atlanta, will spend the rest of
the year developing a blueprint for the work, and construction will
begin in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Mahlon Apgar IV, the assistant Army secretary for installations
and environment, told a Pentagon news conference that the
government expects to save $300 million by putting the housing in
private hands. The companies are expected to invest about $300
million of their own money for housing renovation and construction
at Fort Hood; their revenues will come from the soldiers'
government housing allowances.
</P>
<P>
   Apgar said it would take six to 10 years for all the 5,500
houses at Fort Hood to be renovated or replaced. In that time
period, about 1,140 new homes are to be built. Fort Hood is one of
the biggest U.S. Army bases.
</P>
<P>
   The Fort Hood project is the second in a series of experimental
privatization projects the Army is under taking. The first was at
Fort Carson, Colo., and the next will be at Fort Lewis, Wash.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
