<HEADLINE> Asian American Takes Cabinet Post  </HEADLINE>
By SONYA ROSS
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Norm Mineta literally came across town
Thursday to stand with President Clinton as the nation's first
Asian-American Cabinet secretary. But his real journey began much
farther away, in the internment camps of World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Mineta had just turned 10 when he joined more than 120,000
Japanese-Americans who were rounded up and sent to the camps after
Japan attacked Pearl Harbor in December 1941. He was herded to
Wyoming with his family, in his Cub Scouts uniform.
</P>
<P>
   Even at that tender age, Mineta rejected claims that the move
was for his family's protection. ''I could see the machine guns and
the barbed wire faced inward,'' he once recalled.
</P>
<P>
   In claiming another place in history Thursday, Mineta did not
put those harsh memories on display.
</P>
<P>
   He mentioned his parents, who immigrated from Japan nearly a
century ago only to lose their home and insurance business during
their four-year internment. He mentioned the people he never forgot
as a congressman, those interned Americans for whom he secured an
official apology.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am honored and humbled to be walking across this very
historic threshold with you,'' Mineta told Clinton in an Oval
Office ceremony where the president's choice was announced.
</P>
<P>
   ''The substance of your actions today must never be
underestimated or forgotten. You have the eternal gratitude of not
just Japanese Americans or Asian-Pacific Americans, but I believe
every American.''
</P>
<P>
   If confirmed by the Senate, Mineta, 68, would become the
nation's 33rd Commerce secretary. Among Asian-Americans, Mineta
long has been a man of firsts: first to serve as mayor of a major
city -- his native San Jose, Calif. -- and the first to serve as
chairman of a congressional committee, the House Transportation
committee.
</P>
<P>
   Mineta earned a bachelor of science degree from the University
of California at Berkeley, then was an Army intelligence officer in
Korea for three years. He returned to San Jose to run the Mineta
Insurance Agency and won a city council seat in 1967. He became
mayor in 1971 and was elected to Congress in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   On Capitol Hill, Mineta wrote laws governing airports, transit
systems and roadways, and was an early advocate for high-tech
Silicon Valley in the heart of his district.
</P>
<P>
   But Mineta's heart never strayed far from his people, and he
pushed until he won passage of the Civil Liberties Act of 1988,
through which the United States apologized for the internment camps
and paid reparations of $20,000 to each survivor.
</P>
<P>
   ''Norman Mineta is a true hero and embodies what the American
dream is all about,'' said Sen. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Mineta served 20 years in Congress. In 1995 he stepped down to
take a job as senior vice president of Lockheed Martin Corp., one
of the largest employers in his district.
</P>
<P>
   He announced that decision from the bedroom of the house in San
Jose where he was born, then headed off to run the company's
transportation systems from Bethesda, Md., in suburban Washington.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
