<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 16:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ala. Sen Is Judges' Gatekeeper  </HEADLINE>
By JEFFREY McMURRAY
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Sen. Jeff Sessions' eyes widen and his voice
rises as he reads aloud an essay penned by a law professor.
</P>
<P>
   He slows down when he gets to a particular sentence, shakes his
head in disbelief and reads it again, slower still. In the passage,
Gerard Lynch warns the legal community not to overemphasize words
from ''18th- and 19th-century dictionaries'' when interpreting the
Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Sessions, R-Ala., grins as if he were Hercule Poirot or Sherlock
Holmes and the clues just clicked. Then he pounces, accusing Lynch
of judicial activism, an assault on the Constitution, a call to
legislate from the bench.
</P>
<P>
   Or at least it was a reason to vote against the Democrat's
nomination to the federal bench in New York. Lynch was ultimately
approved on a 63-36 vote.
</P>
<P>
   ''I feel it's important to raise these issues, even if sometimes
you don't win,'' Sessions said. '' ... It's a question of what is
my responsibility as a senator if I have information that this
person wouldn't be a good judge?''
</P>
<P>
   In his four years in Congress, Sessions has gained a reputation
as the senator most likely to object to a judicial nominee.
</P>
<P>
   It's a strange twist for the former U.S. attorney whose own
judicial nomination was scuttled 14 years ago by the Judiciary
Committee on which he now sits. Democratic opponents, led by
then-Alabama Sen. Howell Heflin, questioned his racial sensitivity
in light of his role investigating vote fraud in some predominantly
black Alabama counties.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years later, Heflin retired and Sessions was elected. Since
then, Democrats have watched uneasily as Sessions has sought to
sidetrack some of President Clinton's nominees.
</P>
<P>
   The senator insists he isn't out for revenge.
</P>
<P>
   ''Actually, I'm more sensitive to their personal feelings,''
Sessions said of the nominees. ''If I disagree with someone, I try
to be sure I'm not attacking their integrity. And I don't think
anyone can show that I have.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Sessions opposed Merrick Garland's nomination to
the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia,
saying there was no need to fill the vacancy because the court's
caseload was the country's smallest, an argument critics dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   ''If there's a Republican president, I'll guarantee he won't
find one district that has too low of a caseload,'' said Delaware
Sen. Joseph Biden, who was Judiciary Committee chairman when
Democrats controlled the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Current Chairman Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, said he welcomes the
scrutiny Sessions provides and said he does not believe his
colleague politicizes the process.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've never seen it come out in a vindictive or antagonistic
way,'' Hatch said. ''But he does take the nomination process as
seriously as anyone on the committee.''
</P>
<P>
   Sessions says reviewing judicial appointments is among his
favorite parts of the job. Hatch chuckles at that. Barring the
occasional controversial Supreme Court nominee, it's a fairly
boring process.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing upsets Sessions more than the possibility that a nominee
will try to make laws rather than interpret them.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you can redefine the meaning of the words, you can make the
Constitution say whatever you want it to say,'' he said. ''The only
way you really honor the document is realize it's a contract
between the people and their government, and the words have
meaning.''
</P>
<P>
   Biden says Sessions has helped create an atmosphere in which
politics takes precedence over the qualifications of judicial
nominees.
</P>
<P>
   ''What I worry about most is there are going to be new senators
like Sessions with no institutional memory who will do the same bad
policy,'' Biden said.
</P>
<P>
   Sessions countered: ''I would like to believe that when I leave
this office, I will have played a role in getting superior judges
on the bench.''
</P>
<P>
   ------	   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Sessions' Web site: http://www.senator@sessions.senate.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
