<HEADLINE> Chinse News Agency To Sell Building  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Chinese news agency has agreed to sell a
building it recently bought near the Pentagon, putting to rest U.S.
concerns about possible spy activities.
</P>
<P>
   State Department spokesman Philip Reeker said the Xinhua news
agency notified U.S. officials that it wanted department
authorization to sell the building.
</P>
<P>
   ''We intend to authorize the sale,'' Reeker said Thursday,
adding that Xinhua agreed not to use the building while it is being
marketed.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dana Rohrabacher, R-Calif., one of China's most outspoken
foes on Capitol Hill, said last week that ''what well could be an
arm of Communist Chinese intelligence is now overlooking the
Pentagon and has a bird's eye view electronically of everything
we're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon said at the time that
countermeasures have been developed over the years to thwart
surveillance efforts.
</P>
<P>
   State Department rules require approval of property purchases by
the news agency. But the sale was carried out earlier this month
without State Department knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   The first official word the State Department received about the
transaction occurred last Monday when China delivered a copy of a
May 22 letter that department officials said they had never
received.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're going to work with the Xinhua news agency and the
Chinese embassy to bring this whole matter to a conclusion,''
Reeker said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
