<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 16:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senate passes, Assembly debates budget; Whitman seeks more for surplus </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - The state Senate overwhelmingly approved a
$21.5 billion budget Thursday and Assembly debate on it was under
way by mid-afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   But the stage is set for Gov. Christie Whitman to cut out at
least $25 million by Friday. It would be a fairly small percentage
of overall spending, but could involve eliminating pet projects
inserted by lawmakers last week.
</P>
<P>
   The governor will have until midnight Friday to sign a new
budget for the 2000-2001 fiscal year that begins at 12:01 a.m.
Saturday. If the proposed spending is maintained, it would increase
spending by 10 percent from the budget signed into law one year
ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate passed the budget with only one senator, John Lynch,
D-Middlesex, voting no, though he refused to elaborate on his
objections. Assembly Democrats proclaimed their support for the
budget early in the debate, although a few dissenting votes are
likely there as well.
</P>
<P>
   But there were some strong objections Thursday from one person
with a key vote, the governor, who over the next 24 hours will
exercise her line-item veto to cut items and then sign the document
into law. She is one of the few chief executives in the United
States with the authority to strike spending without further
consulting the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman has insisted on a minimum surplus - a reserve of cash
that remains unspent - of $850 million, and has said she would veto
spending that digs into that surplus too deeply.
</P>
<P>
   During floor debate Thursday, lawmakers proclaimed their budget
bill maintained a surplus of $869 million. However, Whitman
spokesman Peter McDonough said administration officials disagreed
with their mathematics, saying the bill provides for only $825
million for surplus.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute is not over the budget itself but rather concerns
the amount of money being left over from the current fiscal year
which ends at midnight Friday. McDonough said Whitman will make the
changes necessary to restore the full surplus to $850 million,
presumably with cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, the budget increases funding by $157 million for the
30 so-called ''special needs'' districts defined in the Abbott v.
Burke court rulings. Overall school aid will hit $6.65 billion,
with $2.75 billion of it earmarked specifically for the Abbott
districts where the Supreme Court has ordered ''parity'' with the
amount spent on pupils in the state's 100 wealthiest school
systems.
</P>
<P>
   The budget also spends $701 million for the Transportation Trust
Fund, lowering the amount that will need to be financed with
long-term bonds.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Full text of the budget bills, S-2000 and A-1000, are available
at the Office of Legislative Services Web site located at
http://www.njleg.state.nj.us.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
