<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 16:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> RETRANSMITS to add photo tag  </HEADLINE>
By VERENA DOBNIK
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - The Dutch tall ship Eendracht has slipped into
New York harbor - a prelude to a Fourth of July spectacle billed as
the largest maritime event in peacetime.
</P>
<P>
   The vessel, docked Thursday in Manhattan's South Street Seaport
awaiting Opsail 2000, ''was the first in,'' said Eric Ray, a
spokesman for the latest - and largest - gathering of wind-powered
tall ships.
</P>
<P>
   It harkens an era when commerce poured into New York from around
the world by sea. Little more than a century ago, a forest of masts
rose above the same piers near Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   This year, about 150 tall ships from at least 50 nations will
share the waters with 40 modern warships of 23 navies - a weeklong
spectacle expected to draw more than 4 million people. It begins on
Sunday, with the arrival of the modern naval fleet in the harbor.
</P>
<P>
   ''The beauty of a ship is when she's driven by the wind,'' said
retired Admiral Paul Welling, a 35-year U.S. Coast Guard veteran
and OpSail's chief operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   In a tip to modern times, each tall ship is now equipped with an
auxiliary engine. Timing the complex display means the
antique-style vessels will be engine-powered as they move into
place, with sailors perched atop the rigging, Welling said Thursday
at a Manhattan briefing.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the tall ships will file into the harbor in formation on
Monday, to be berthed on the Hudson River and at the South Street
Seaport.
</P>
<P>
   Fourth of July festivities will begin early, with President
Clinton present for the International Naval Review of a fleet with
almost 10,000 U.S. and foreign military personnel.
</P>
<P>
   Starting at 8:05 a.m., Clinton plans to board the guided missile
cruiser USS Hue City to review the cruisers, destroyers and
frigates anchored in a 17-mile line from the George Washington
Bridge to the Verrazano Narrows.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. fleet will be blessed by the chaplains aboard each,
using language that goes back to George Washington's time, said
Capt. Woody Berzins, a Navy spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after 10 a.m., the president is to move to the aircraft
carrier USS John F. Kennedy, anchored off the Statue of Liberty.
Passing by at about the same time will be the flagship of the
waterborne parade, the U.S. Coast Guard training barque, Eagle,
originally seized from Nazi Germany in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   ''You'll see everything from the technology of today's ships to
the majesty of the tall ships,'' said Berzins, the Navy spokesman.
''It captures history, the present and the future - all in one
moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with other Navy guests on the flight deck, the president
will watch the procession of schooners, brigantines, barques and
square-riggers as they pass up the harbor, while 80 aircraft buzz
overhead.
</P>
<P>
   On the JFK, Clinton and other guests will be entertained by 43
performers from Broadway shows.
</P>
<P>
   The aging, conventionally powered carrier, based at Norfolk,
Va., is allowed to enter New York harbor, from which the Navy's
newer, nuclear-powered carriers are barred.
</P>
<P>
   To watch the maritime extravaganza, as many as 70,000 other
craft are expected to flood area waters - nearly three times the
number at the 1986 Statue of Liberty centennial, according to the
Coast Guard.
</P>
<P>
   The first tall ship in port this week was the Eendracht. Built
in the Hague in 1989, the 194-foot ship was docked at Pier 16 in
lower Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the official vessels participating are used for naval
training, including the Chilean navy's 371-foot four-master
Esmerelda and Germany's 295-foot barque Gorch Fock, a sister ship
to Eagle.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the USS Mount Whitney, the USS Nassau and five
other U.S. warships, American vessels include the Amistad, a
recreation of a famed 19th century slave ship, and the HMS Rose, a
replica of an Elizabethan-era vessel raised at Portsmouth Harbor.
</P>
<P>
   Past naval reviews commemorated events in U.S. history, while
this year's joint event marks the Navy's official observance of the
millennium, dubbed ''A Celebration of Seapower for the
Millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   OpSail is to be capped by a spectacular July 4 fireworks display
using 13 barges at five different harbor locations.
</P>
<P>
   New York is the main port of call in the tall ships' nine-week
coastal cruise from San Juan, Puerto Rico on May 25 to Portland,
Maine, on July 31, with stops in Miami, Norfolk, Va.; Baltimore,
Philadelphia and New London, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Operation Sail, established by President John F. Kennedy in 1961
to promote international relations and cultural exchange, also has
organized the 1964 New York World's Fair, the U.S. Bicentennial in
1976, and the Christopher Columbus Quincentennial in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.inr2000.navy.mil
</P>
<P>
   http://www.opsailnyc.org
</P>
<P>
   http://www.uscg.mil/d1/sailevent2000
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-29-00 1659 </TRAILER>
