<DOCNO> APW20000629.0069 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 17:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senate approves right-to-die attorney for judgeship  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - The New Jersey Senate has approved
right-to-die attorney Paul Armstrong for a judgeship in Somerset
County.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate on Thursday also confirmed appointments of Glenn
Wenzel, David Waks and Thomas Brogan for three judgeships in
Passaic County. Christine Allen-Jackson was confirmed for a
judgeship in Gloucester County.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-nine of 428 positions still remain unfilled.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the Senate Judiciary Committee unanimously approved
Armstrong over objections from the New Jersey Right to Life.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong has been at the forefront of legal cases dealing with
biomedical ethics.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong successfully argued for the family of Karen Ann
Quinlan to disconnect her from respirator, leading to New Jersey
Supreme Court's 1976 landmark decision granting the right to die,
the nation's first such court ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Quinlan had slipped into a coma at a party in April 1975. She
died in a Morris Plains nursing home in 1985.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
