<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 17:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Public help still needed to combat virus  </HEADLINE>
By DENISE LAVOIE
<TEXT>
<P>
   WESTPORT, Conn. (AP) - Although no evidence of the West
Nile-like strain of the encephalitis virus has been found in
Connecticut this year, state environmental officials are again
asking for the public's help in reducing the mosquito population.
</P>
<P>
   Since an outbreak of the virus last year, state officials have
intensified a mosquito trapping, testing and larvicide program. The
virus did not cause any human illness in Connecticut, but infected
72 people in New York, killing seven.
</P>
<P>
   The virus, which first surfaced in the Western Hemisphere last
year, also killed hundreds of birds in New York, New Jersey and
Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   This season four crows in Rockland County, N.Y., tested positive
for the virus. Another crow tested positive in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut environmental officials held a public education
session at Sherwood Island State Park on Thursday to reassure
residents and describe efforts to reduce the likelihood of another
outbreak.
</P>
<P>
   They asked homeowners to help eliminate mosquito breeding
grounds by removing any standing water on their property - in
gutters, old tires, sandboxes and even items as small as flower
pots.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our best defense against West Nile virus ... is protection,''
said First Selectman Diane Farrell.
</P>
<P>
   Theodore Andreadis, chief entomologist for the Connecticut
Agricultural Experiment Station, said the state has tested 11,000
mosquitoes trapped at 73 locations around the state.
</P>
<P>
   ''As of today, we have no evidence of West Nile virus activity
in mosquitoes,'' Andreadis said.
</P>
<P>
   Tests on 54 dead birds have also come back negative.
</P>
<P>
   Iris Nemni, a Westport resident, said she attended the public
briefing to learn more about preventing another outbreak.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm concerned a little bit ... not dramatically though,'' she
said. ''I know they are taking care of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Michele Sullivan, a spokeswoman for the state Department of
Environmental Protection, said the state next week will begin
airing 30-second television spots to increase public awareness
about the virus.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan said stations in Connecticut and New York have agreed
to run the ads, which show a couple emptying standing water from
various items outside their home. Radio announcements are planned
for later this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Most people who become infected either show no reaction or
become mildly ill with flu-like symptoms. The vast majority suffer
no long-term problems. The most vulnerable are the elderly and
those with immune deficiencies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
