<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 17:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SEC investigates Xerox for alleged accounting irregularities in Mexico division </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) - In the latest in a string of problems,
Xerox Corp. is being investigated by the U.S. Securities and
Exchange Commission for accounting irregularities in the company's
Mexico operations.
</P>
<P>
   The business machines maker announced the investigation
Thursday, but released no specifics, saying only that the SEC was
looking into ''accounting issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, the company said problems in its Mexican
business were expected to drag down second-quarter earnings by
about 6 cents per share. At that time, a company spokeswoman said
Xerox was doing an internal investigation related to problems with
bad debt.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Xerox spokesman Bill McKee said the company could
not reveal details of either the SEC investigation or its own
internal investigation. He said the company would reveal details of
the investigations when it releases its second-quarter earnings on
July 26.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC can bring civil actions in federal court. McKee would
not comment on whether a separate criminal probe is ongoing.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will certainly cooperate in any way,'' McKee said of the
SEC probe. ''Because this is a formal, legal investigation, we are
really limited in what we can say.''
</P>
<P>
   The company's Mexico operations pulled in revenues of about $400
million in 1999. There are more than 3,000 Xerox employees in
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last year, Xerox has been beset with problems that have
depressed earnings and the company's stock, including a cumbersome
realignment of its sales force along industry lines rather than
geographic boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   In May, the company asked Chief Executive Rick Thoman to step
down after just 13 months at the helm. His firing came a month
after the company reported a $243 million loss in the first
quarter. The loss had been expected following the announcement in
March that Xerox would lay off 5,200 employees and close several
plants as part of an effort to cut costs to remain competitive with
rivals Hewlett-Packard and Canon.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, the company's stock fell nearly 19 percent
the day it warned that second-quarter earnings would be well below
Wall Street expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Xerox said its earnings per share, before unusual items, would
likely be near the first-quarter level of 30 cents per share. A
recent First Call/Thomson Financial's survey found analysts
expecting Xerox to earn 42 cents a share in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   John Heine, a spokesman for the SEC, said the commission does
not confirm nor deny investigations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
