<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Internet Retailers, FTC Settle  </HEADLINE>
By D. IAN HOPPER
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Federal Trade Commission agreed Thursday
to a settlement in the case of three large Internet retailers it
said was engaged in deceptive advertising in the sale of low-cost
computer systems.
</P>
<P>
   In a consent agreement, the FTC said the companies, Buy.com of
Aliso Viejo, Calif., Value America in Charlottesville Va., and
Office Depot, based in Delray Beach, Fla., ran ads that did not
disclose the true price of computer systems.
</P>
<P>
   The consent agreement is a settlement, and does not mean that
the companies pleaded guilty of any crime. The agreement is
expected to take effect on July 31. If the companies continue their
controversial advertising after then, they would be subject to
substantial fines.
</P>
<P>
   At issue are the once-popular ''free'' or cheap computers that
include substantial rebates based on the purchase of three years of
Internet service with a provider such as CompuServe or the
Microsoft Network. The advertising included in some cases tiny
print with the many restrictions, such as the cost of the Internet
subscription or penalties for early cancellation, or no disclosure
at all of the strings attached.
</P>
<P>
   ''You shouldn't need a Ph.D. to figure out the cost of a PC,''
said Jodie Bernstein, the head of the FTC's consumer protection
division. ''These advertisers should have done a better job of
disclosing the details so consumers could figure out the deal. The
fact is that consumers and businesses all benefit when disclosures
are prominently placed and in plain English.''
</P>
<P>
   Buy.com, one of the top five e-commerce companies with 1999
revenues of almost $600 million, said in a statement that it
thought customers understood the intricacies of the deal, and that
they received no customer complaints.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are glad we were able to work together with the FTC to
resolve this issue,'' said Mitch Hill, Buy.com's CFO. ''As soon as
we became aware of the concern with the computer advertisement,
Buy.com pulled the ads to eliminate the possibility of any
potential confusion.''
</P>
<P>
   In the FTC's complaint against Buy.com, the commission took
issue with both print and online ads that advertised a Compaq
computer at $269. At the bottom of some of the ads, the company
said that the $269 cost included two rebates -- one from CompuServe
in return for a 3-year Internet contract, and one from Compaq.
Since the customer must pay for 3 years of service at $21.95 per
month, the total cost of the computer is $790.20. In other ads,
there was no disclosure of the rebates at all.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC also took issue with the fact that CompuServe does not
have local access phone numbers in all areas, so users may have to
pay a long-distance charge.
</P>
<P>
   A statement from Value America said that it would change its
practices ''to ensure consumers are able to make better informed
decisions about purchases involving price rebates.''
</P>
<P>
   The FTC said Value America also failed to disclose that the
Internet service provider rebates would take 12-17 weeks to arrive
and that the company failed to ship products within the promised
delivery time.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC also alleged that both Value America and Office Depot,
the world's largest seller of office products, advertised that
their ''free'' computer system offer included a free monitor. The
monitor had to be bought separately. Office Depot representatives
did not return a call for comment Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-29-00 1729 </TRAILER>
