<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 17:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lazio counterattacks in controversy over missed House vote  </HEADLINE>
By FRANK ELTMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   GARDEN CITY, N.Y. (AP) - Rep. Rick Lazio derided Hillary Rodham
Clinton on Thursday for running a TV ad criticizing him for a
missed House vote, saying she was at a fund-raiser for a Democratic
congressman who was skipping the same June 15 vote.
</P>
<P>
   ''She clearly knew by the time she went on the attack against me
... that she didn't have clean hands on this issue,'' Lazio said in
a telephone interview from Washington. ''What she's trying to do is
fool the people of New York and I just think her lack of straight
talk is going to reverberate.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton campaign fired back that Lazio is trying to shift
focus away from himself. ''I just think it's downright sad that
Congressman Lazio would divert attention from the fact that he
missed this critical vote,'' said Clinton campaign spokesman Howard
Wolfson.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, the Republican candidate for U.S. Senate, missed the vote
on a $10 million funding bill that would have established a 2
million barrel home heating oil reserve. The bill, which he
championed, was defeated 195-193. Lazio was flying back to New York
for campaign events when the vote took place around 9 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   He was one of 47 House members, including five New York
Democrats, who missed the vote. The other New Yorkers were Reps.
Eliot Engel, Charles Rangel, Jose Serrano, Jerrold Nadler and Nydia
Velazquez.
</P>
<P>
   Engel skipped the vote to attend a fund-raiser for his campaign,
held in Westchester County, which Clinton also attended.
</P>
<P>
   Engel, in his re-election bid, faces a Democratic primary
challenge by state Sen. Larry Seabrook. Engel said in a statement
that he was told by House GOP leaders there would be no votes after
6 p.m. that day.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Republican leadership misled many members of Congress,
including their own, by not telling members that votes were being
scheduled for after 6 p.m. until members were leaving Washington
for their districts,'' Engel said. ''The people of the northeast
must be wondering if they were hurt by Republican ineptness or
Republican duplicity in misleading members about when voting would
take place.''
</P>
<P>
   Two days after the missed vote, Lazio contended that there would
be occasions during his abbreviated Senate campaign when he might
miss House votes. The Long Island congressman entered the race in
mid-May after New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani dropped out to have
more time for treatment of his prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're going to miss some votes, because I need to get around
the state,'' he said then. ''We got into this race very late. It's
the nature of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The following week, the Clinton campaign released a television
ad in upstate New York that criticized Lazio over the missed oil
reserve vote:
</P>
<P>
   ''Congress just defeated a plan - by only two votes - to lower
home heating oil costs for New York and the Northeast. How did Rick
Lazio vote? He didn't. He skipped the vote. Rick Lazio. The more
you know, the more you wonder.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio on Thursday questioned Clinton's truthfulness.
</P>
<P>
   ''For her to know that she was at a fund-raiser with a
Democratic member who missed that vote and turn around and to try
and place the blame on me,'' he said, ''I think it speaks once
again to the issue of character, integrity and truthfulness.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolfson countered that Lazio ''will do anything he can to avoid
taking responsibility. He should stop pointing fingers and take
responsibility. ... The last time I looked Hillary Clinton was not
a member of Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio repeated Thursday that he is not considering resigning
from the House to avoid criticism on future votes he might miss
while campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am committed to filling out my term and serving the people
who sent me here,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-29-00 1729 </TRAILER>
