<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 17:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bill requires systems in all college and university dorm rooms  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - With technical differences ironed out, the
state Assembly voted unanimously Thursday to require fire
sprinklers in every dorm room at every college and university in
New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Public and private colleges would have to install the fire
safety systems over the next four years.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation is in response to a fire at Seton Hall
University in January that killed three students and injured 62
others.
</P>
<P>
   ''Clearly this legislature has a responsibility to take
appropriate action to ensure this unfortunate tragedy does not
happen again, because it could very well have been prevented,''
said Assemblyman John V. Kelly, R-Essex, a bill sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Christie Whitman plans to sign the bill Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''I commend the Legislature for so quickly passing this
important legislation,'' Whitman said in a statement. ''I look
forward to signing this bill to provide a measure of comfort to
parents who are sending their young people away to school.''
</P>
<P>
   Several colleges and universities, including Seton Hall, are
already moving ahead with installing sprinklers in every room in
time for the fall semester.
</P>
<P>
   Rutgers, Rowan University in Glassboro, William Paterson
University in Wayne and Seton Hall have announced plans to put fire
sprinklers in all or some dorm rooms by fall.
</P>
<P>
   At Rutgers, nearly 2,000 students will find new sprinklers in
their rooms on some campuses in September.
</P>
<P>
   The original Senate version called for a two-year deadline, but
lawmakers extended the time frame after school officials and
contractors complained the schedule was too tight.
</P>
<P>
   Colleges and universities would also have to submit a plan to
the state Department of Community Affairs four months after the
bill is signed into law.
</P>
<P>
   The measure would appropriate $90 million to help pay for the
sprinklers. Public and private colleges and universities would get
zero-interest loans, while boarding schools, military academies and
other schools that have dorms would have to repay the loans at 2
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The bill allows exemptions for certain buildings. That would
most likely apply to ''very small'' buildings, state officials have
said.
</P>
<P>
   State officials estimate that more than 36,000 college dorm beds
are located in rooms without sprinklers.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have heard all the arguments. We have debated the merits of
multiple plans and time limits. Now, it is finally time to get this
bill signed and see these sprinklers installed,'' said state Sen.
John J. Matheussen, R-Gloucester.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am hopeful Gov. Whitman takes the opportunity to sign this
bill quickly and gives colleges and universities a not-too-subtle
message not to wait four years to do this,'' said Sen. John A.
Girgenti, D-Passaic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-29-00 1730 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000629.0084 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 17:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Congressman Gets Cabinet Post  </HEADLINE>
By TERENCE HUNT
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton nominated former Rep. Norman
Mineta, an executive with America's biggest defense contractor, to
lead the Commerce Department and become the first Asian-American
Cabinet secretary.
</P>
<P>
   ''He brings an in-depth understanding of American business and a
strong sense of the needs of our high-tech economy,'' the president
said at an Oval Office announcement ceremony Thursday. ''But he
also has a deep concern for people, for people in places who are
not yet fully participating in this economy.''
</P>
<P>
   As a former member of Congress, Mineta is expected to win strong
support in the Senate. If confirmed, he would succeed William
Daley, who is stepping down July 15 to run Vice President Al Gore's
presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Mineta, a Japanese-American who spent his childhood in a Wyoming
internment camp during World War II, served 21 years in the House
representing the Silicon Valley area surrounding San Jose in
Northern California. He rose to become chairman of the House Public
Works and Transportation Committee in 1993 but lost his title after
Republicans won control of the House in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Mineta resigned midterm in 1995 to join Lockheed Martin, the
nation's largest defense contractor, as senior vice president of
its transportation systems and services division.
</P>
<P>
   Although Lockheed Martin received $12.7 billion in defense
contracts in fiscal year 1999, Mineta role was in helping the
company lessen its dependence on a shrinking Pentagon pie. His
company, Lockheed Martin IMS, builds and operates electronic toll
collection systems designed to allow vehicles to go through booths
without stopping.
</P>
<P>
   In Congress, Mineta was a leader of efforts to build high-tech
transportation systems. His handiwork was apparent in the 1991
transportation law, which included $660 million for research into
intelligent highway systems.
</P>
<P>
   Mineta's nomination raised questions about how he would distance
himself from decisions affecting his former company.
</P>
<P>
   ''Certainly there is the potential for conflict there,'' said
Charles Lewis, head of the Center for Public Integrity, a
government watchdog group. ''The question is how does he handle
that potential. If he's smart he will recuse himself for a period
of time. The normal time is usually a year or two years although
some have done even longer than that.''
</P>
<P>
   In Mineta's case, the Clinton administration will leave office
in less than seven months.
</P>
<P>
   White House press secretary Joe Lockhart said Mineta would abide
by all relevant ethics rules.
</P>
<P>
   In his remarks, Mineta took issue with the notion that he would
not have enough time in his job to make a difference. ''Six months
is a virtual eternity in the new economy,'' Mineta said.
</P>
<P>
   The son of immigrants from Japan, Mineta said his nomination was
the triumph of the American dream.
</P>
<P>
   ''The substance of your actions today must never be
underestimated or forgotten,'' Mineta said. ''Mr. President, you
have the eternal gratitude of not just Japanese Americans or
Asian-Pacific Americans but I believe every American.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that Mineta, leaving the internment camp after the
war, ''vowed to work to make sure that kind of injustice could
never happen to anyone else.'' Tracing Mineta's political career in
San Jose as the first Asian-American mayor of a major American city
and then in Congress, Clinton said, ''He never stopped fighting for
justice.''
</P>
<P>
   The president noted that Mineta's effort led to legislation
which provided an apology and compensation for every survivor of
the wartime internment camps.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: Clinton announcement:
http://www.whitehouse.gov/library/PressReleases.cgi
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-29-00 1730 </TRAILER>
