<DOCNO> APW20000629.0087 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 17:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Big Business Pushes Trade Vote  </HEADLINE>
By TOM RAUM
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- U.S. business leaders stepped up their
campaign for a Senate vote next month on a bill to expand trade
with China, voicing fears that it might wind up a casualty of
election-year politics if further delayed.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are calling on the Senate leadership to schedule the vote
and complete action this summer before the upcoming nominating
conventions,'' said Cal Cohen, president of the Emergency Committee
for American Trade, a business coalition that is pushing the
China-trade bill.
</P>
<P>
   The House passed the bill to extend permanent normal trade
relations to China in May on a 237-197 vote, but it has since
languished in the Senate, despite wide bipartisan support.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., earlier this week
said he hoped to bring up the bill in July, but declined to set a
timetable. He has suggested that the Senate first must work on a
set of crucial spending bills needed to keep the government
functioning.
</P>
<P>
   If the China trade bill dies because Congress runs out of time,
''America will pay the consequences for decades,'' said U.S.
Chamber of Commerce President Thomas Donohue.
</P>
<P>
   In a Senate speech, Sen. Max Baucus, D-Mont., a leading Senate
sponsor of the bill, also called on Lott ''to set a date certain in
July'' on the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ''Prompt passage and enactment of this bill should be a top
bipartisan priority,'' Baucus said.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the legislation hope that the Senate will accept
the House-passed version and not adopt additional amendments that
would further delay proceedings and require yet another House vote.
</P>
<P>
   Lott announced earlier this week that one major obstacle had
been cleared with the scheduling of a separate vote on a proposal
by Sens. Fred Thompson, R-Tenn., and Robert Torricelli, D-N.J.,
that could lead to sanctions against Beijing for spreading nuclear
weapons or missile technology to other countries.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange, Thompson and Torricelli promised not to offer their
plan -- strongly opposed by the Clinton administration -- to the
China trade bill.
</P>
<P>
   But other potential amendments, both from the political left and
the political right, threatened to drag out debate on the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The China trade bills are H.R. 4444 and S. 2277.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: White House: http://www.chinapntr.gov
</P>
<P>
   AFL-CIO: http://www.aflcio.org/publ/press2000/pr0222.htm
</P>
