<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Animal Park Owner Aspinall Dies  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- John Aspinall, a millionaire gambling tycoon and
owner of two wild animal parks, died Thursday of cancer, his family
said. He was 74.
</P>
<P>
   Aspinall was born in India in 1926 and moved with his family to
England at age 6.
</P>
<P>
   He was already a well-known high roller during his student days
at Oxford University, and in the 1950's became a regular patron of
London's black market gaming clubs.
</P>
<P>
   By the time gambling was legalized in the 1960's, Aspinall was
operating traveling Baccarat games for the privileged classes, and
expanded his operations to include gaming rooms in London, New
Zealand and France.
</P>
<P>
   A large win at the horse races helped Aspinall buy his first
home in 1956 -- an 18th-century country house near Canterbury in
southeast England. Aspinall used the 40-acre property as a base to
collect gorillas, tigers, elephants and rhinos.
</P>
<P>
   In 1973, when the collection became too large, Aspinall bought
an early 20th century mansion in nearby Port Lympne on 275 acres.
Two years later, he opened both animal parks to the public and
eventually transferred ownership to a charity foundation under his
name.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have never been able to afford anything in my life. I just
take plunges and hope the gods smile on me later. They always have,
until now,'' Aspinall said in a television interview after he was
diagnosed with cancer several years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Aspinall's parks were lauded as successful breeding grounds, and
over the years staff oversaw the birth of 73 gorillas and six black
rhinos.
</P>
<P>
   But Aspinall's game parks were best known for their unorthodox
approach to animal management, in particular his policy of
encouraging close personal relationships between staff and wild
animals.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors regularly saw keepers playing with tigers or gorillas,
which Aspinall believed helped the animals' emotional well-being.
But his philosophy was not without controversy.
</P>
<P>
   Over the decades, five employees died while caring for the
animals. The latest victim was a Port Lympne gamekeeper who was
crushed by an elephant in February.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Canterbury's city council took Aspinall to court,
arguing that keepers should be banned from entering cages unless
the animals were young or immobilized. Aspinall won the case.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Aspinall was undergoing surgery for throat and
jaw cancer at London's Royal Marsden Hospital. He would battle the
disease for the next four years.
</P>
<P>
   ''Immortality comes from your genes, provided you pass them on.
I am amazed that any religion can demand more than that,'' Aspinall
said in February. ''I have two stout sons, one of whom has bred and
another who will breed, and a daughter who has bred. So I've no
wish to float through space as a soul. It is just a greedy
illusion.''
</P>
<P>
   Aspinall is survived by his wife Sarah, two sons Damian and
Bassa, daughter Amanda and two stepsons Jason and Amos Courage.
Funeral arrangements were not immediately available.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
