<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 17:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Psychiatrist Says Elian Needs Help  </HEADLINE>
By PAULINE JELINEK
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Once he was reunited with his father, Elian
Gonzalez was able to regain the ''life of a child and not an icon''
but he will still need help in Cuba to cope with the trauma of
losing his mother at sea, his U.S. government-appointed
psychiatrist said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In her first interview since finishing consultations with the
6-year-old shipwreck survivor, Dr. Paulina Kernberg told The
Associated Press the boy lived with fear, uncertainty and stress in
his first five months in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   He spent that time in Miami's Little Havana neighborhood, where
his America relatives cared for him and tried to get him asylum
against return to communist Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ''As things unfolded, there was always the fear that somebody
was going to come and take him away,'' said Kernberg, a child
psychiatrist and professor of psychiatry appointed to the case by
the Immigration and Naturalization Service.
</P>
<P>
   Elian was kept away from school, there were barricades around
the house, and his caretakers -- great-uncle Lazaro and cousin
Marisleysis Gonzalez -- eventually cut back on his outings out of
their own fears for his safety.
</P>
<P>
   Kernberg said Elian's fear abated after he was seized from that
home and reunited April 22 with his father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez,
stepmother, Nersy, and infant half brother Hianny.
</P>
<P>
   ''Beyond a doubt he felt safe ... and I think the people who
provided that were his father and stepmother,'' Kernberg said,
calling them ''very receptive and sensitive.''
</P>
<P>
   The visit by Elian's Cuban playmates restored even more of his
past life, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''His life regained a sense of safety with a routine appropriate
to the life of a child and not an icon,'' said Kernberg, director
of child and adolescent psychiatry at New York-Presbyterian
Hospital and professor of psychiatry at the Cornell University
Medical College.
</P>
<P>
   Kernberg was among the doctors appointed to help the warring
sides of the family arrange an emotionally smooth transfer of the
boy back to his father. When negotiations failed and the boy was
taken from Miami, she visited Elian and his reunited Cuban family
every two weeks in Maryland and the Washington area.
</P>
<P>
   Her task was to check on how they were doing and be available
for counseling if needed, she said, adding that her last visit was
June 19.
</P>
<P>
   She said Nersy, ''who has been quiet in all this process,'' is a
more important figure than she appeared as the saga played out
publicly.
</P>
<P>
   ''She is the stepmother with whom Elian has been very close and
spent most of the time before he arrived in the United States,''
Kernberg said. ''She is really very important, a real surrogate,
more than a surrogate mother.''
</P>
<P>
   Elian also developed ''a very important relationship'' with his
Miami relatives, she said, adding that while Elian doesn't
necessarily ''need them'' in his future, she hopes the two sides of
the family can reconcile.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a good extended family, one that we would wish for
every child to have,'' Kernberg said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Unfortunately ... the grown-ups couldn't negotiate, come to
terms, accept differences and keep the tie, which is what happens
to many cases of divorce.''
</P>
<P>
   But most important for Elian, Kernberg said, is that he have
help from his family or professionals in Cuba in talking through
the ''big scare'' and trauma of seeing his mother drown in their
failed crossing to America.
</P>
<P>
   ''I trust that they will have ... our professional counterparts
there to continue the work that the little boy will still need to
... (talk through) the grief, the loss of his mother and all the
stresses.''
</P>
<P>
   Those included ''being without his father and family, of not
knowing when he would see them again, of being in the limelight day
and night and being in the role that went beyond a regular child's
role.''
</P>
<P>
   ''He was turned into an icon and that was stressful,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Kernberg said Elian has ''begun some of this process of
mourning, of grief.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Irwin Redlener, a pediatrician who in April also consulted
with the government on Elian's case, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   Redlener visited the Cuban family socially for two hours on May
31 and said Elian ''looked terrific ... like a completely normal
6-year-old.''
</P>
<P>
   ''There was nothing ... that would suggest he would need
anything special except to get some stability with his family,
going to school and being home,'' he said, except for the help with
his mother's death.
</P>
<P>
   Redlener is a professor of pediatrics at Albert Einstein College
of Medicine and president and director of community pediatrics at
the Children's Hospital at Montefiore in New York. He assembled the
panel of mental health specialists, including Kernberg, at the
request of the INS.
</P>
<P>
   ''At the end of the day, this is a little boy who had an
unbelievably traumatic experience of watching his mother die at
sea,'' Redlener said.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a child I would pay close attention to.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
