<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Courts To Study State Abortion Bans  </HEADLINE>
By LAURIE ASSEO
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Some abortion foes acknowledge their states'
bans on ''partial-birth'' abortion are doomed by a new Supreme
Court ruling. But others vow to fight for some type of restriction
that would survive legal challenge.
</P>
<P>
   A day after striking down Nebraska's law as an undue burden on
women's right to end their pregnancies, the Supreme Court acted
Thursday on three other state laws that sought to prohibit the
procedure opponents call partial-birth abortion.
</P>
<P>
   The justices ordered a federal appeals court that had upheld
laws from Illinois and Wisconsin to reconsider them in light of the
standards set by Wednesday's 5-4 ruling in the Nebraska case. And,
in one of many orders issued in the wake of the 1999-2000 term, the
justices let stand a federal appeals court ruling that struck down
Iowa's partial-birth abortion law.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, state officials and advocates on both sides of the
abortion issue are examining the Nebraska decision for its impact
on laws in their states.
</P>
<P>
   ''In practical terms, it means that the South Dakota statute is
unenforceable,'' said state Attorney General Mark Barnett. ''Our
hands are tied. They've expressed the law and we must follow it.''
</P>
<P>
   Kansas state Rep. Tony Powell, an anti-abortion leader, said,
''I will be honest with you, I don't know what we will do. ... Am I
giving up? No, not yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans in Congress also are looking to retool their
proposed legislation. ''This opinion will be studied intensely,''
said House Judiciary Chairman Henry Hyde, R-Ill.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton vetoed proposed partial-birth abortion bans in
1996 and 1997, saying they did not provide adequate exceptions to
protect the health of the mother. Both times, Congress failed to
override the veto.
</P>
<P>
   The justices said the Nebraska law could criminalize other
abortion procedures besides the one opponents said they were
targeting. The law's other big flaw, the court said, was its lack
of an exemption to allow the procedure if a doctor concludes it is
the best way to preserve a woman's health.
</P>
<P>
   Gloria Feldt, national president of Planned Parenthood, said
Thursday, ''Our lawyers believe that most, if not all, of the laws
would almost inevitably be unconstitutional under this ruling.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, she added, ''We assume we will be back in court on
the question of whether there is any state interest that will
justify a more narrowly written'' ban on the procedure.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Nebraska, 30 states enacted bans on partial-birth
abortion. Many of those laws have been blocked or invalidated by
lower courts.
</P>
<P>
   Alaska's law was invalidated by a state judge a few months after
it was enacted in 1997. After Wednesday's ruling, state Attorney
General Bruce Botelho said he instructed the state's lawyers to
withdraw an appeal in the Alaska Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Dorinda Bordlee, an attorney who argued in favor of Louisiana's
law, said the justices' ruling effectively kills her state's
statute.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a very extreme decision which has the effect of striking
down the partial-birth abortion bans all over the nation,'' Bordlee
said.
</P>
<P>
   Wisconsin Attorney General James Doyle said Thursday his state's
law clearly is unconstitutional under the Nebraska ruling. ''The
court premised its holding on its view that in order to be
constitutional the law must protect the women's health. The
Wisconsin law does not,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wisconsin Gov. Tommy Thompson said if his state's law is thrown
out when reconsidered, he will ask lawmakers to pass another one
that might have a better chance of meeting constitutional
standards.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Right to Life spokeswoman Gen Wilson said the Supreme
Court's ruling ''isn't a great blow to Georgia because our
partial-birth abortion law was virtually impotent.''
</P>
<P>
   Following a court challenge by doctors to the 1997 law, Georgia
officials agreed to interpret it to ban only abortions performed
after the fetus could live outside the womb, and to include an
exception to protect the mother's health.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Sandra Day O'Connor, who provided the fifth vote to
strike down Nebraska's law, said a partial-birth abortion law could
pass muster if it were limited to that particular procedure and
included an exception to preserve the mother's life and health.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Anthony M. Kennedy, a co-author with O'Connor of the
court's 1992 ruling that upheld abortion rights, wrote in dissent
Wednesday that her assurance that Nebraska could redraft the law
was ''meaningless.''
</P>
<P>
   Laws in Ohio and Utah seek to target only one procedure, and
both have an exception designed to protect the woman's life and
health.
</P>
<P>
   In North Dakota, Jane Bovard, administrator of the Red River
Women's Clinic in Fargo, said she hoped the Supreme Court's ruling
would prompt another look at North Dakota's ban on the procedure.
</P>
<P>
   ''We just have to keep fighting every time they come up with one
of these ways to challenge'' abortion rights, Bovard said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: For the Supreme Court's ruling in Stenberg v.
Carhart: http://supct.law.cornell.edu/supct/html/99-830.ZS.html
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
