<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 18:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senate, Assembly pass budget but Whitman seeks more for surplus  </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Both houses of the Legislature
overwhelmingly approved a $21.5 billion budget Thursday, but the
stage is set for Gov. Christie Whitman to cut out part of it in
order to enlarge the surplus she wants for the next fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   The governor is expected to use her line-item veto power to
remove at least $25 million by Friday, a fairly small percentage of
overall spending but a cut that could touch some of the pet
projects lawmakers inserted last week.
</P>
<P>
   Senate President Donald DiFrancesco said it was a tiny amount in
the overall scheme of things. ''This is her prerogative, and I
don't think it is a major cause of concern,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The governor is scheduled to sign the budget Friday afternoon.
The state constitution gives her until midnight Friday for the
2000-2001 fiscal year that begins at 12:01 a.m. Saturday. If the
budget remains largely intact, as expected, it would increase
spending by 10 percent from the budget signed into law one year
ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate passed the budget with only one ''no'' vote from Sen.
John Lynch, D-Middlesex, who criticized Whitman and the Republicans
for doing too little to reduce debt. ''The theme of this budget
cycle is one of missed opportunities,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Assembly passed it 75-4 with Democratic leaders proclaiming
their support for it early in Thursday's debate. Two Democrats and
two Republicans voted no.
</P>
<P>
   One of them, Assemblyman Joseph Suliga, D-Union, condemned the
increase in spending at a time when local towns and schools are
being held to much tighter caps. ''My parents always taught me if
you earn a little more, you save a little more for the future. This
budget does not do that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There were also strong objections Thursday from one person with
a key say in the matter, Whitman, one of the few chief executives
in the United States who can use the line-item veto without further
consulting the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman has insisted on a minimum surplus - a reserve of cash
that remains unspent - of $850 million, and has said she would veto
spending that digs into that surplus too deeply.
</P>
<P>
   During floor debate Thursday, lawmakers proclaimed their budget
bill maintained a surplus of $869 million. However, Whitman
spokesman Peter McDonough said administration officials disagreed
with their mathematics, saying the bill provides for only $825
million for surplus.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute is not over the budget itself but rather concerns
the amount of money being left over from the current fiscal year
which ends at midnight Friday. McDonough said Whitman will make the
changes necessary to restore the full surplus to $850 million,
presumably with cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, the budget increases funding by $157 million for the
30 so-called ''special needs'' districts defined in the Abbott v.
Burke court rulings. Overall school aid will hit $6.65 billion,
with $2.75 billion of it earmarked specifically for the Abbott
districts where the Supreme Court has ordered ''parity'' with the
amount spent on pupils in the state's 100 wealthiest school
systems.
</P>
<P>
   The budget also spends $701 million for the Transportation Trust
Fund, lowering the amount that will need to be financed with
long-term bonds.
</P>
<P>
   --:
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Full text of the budget bills, S-2000 and A-1000, are available
at the Office of Legislative Services Web site located at
http://www.njleg.state.nj.us.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
