<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico Signs Free Trade Pact  </HEADLINE>
By AMPARO TREJO
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Mexico signed a free trade pact Thursday with
three Central American nations, extending a free-market crusade
that president Ernesto Zedillo said should lead to Latin American
unity.
</P>
<P>
   ''The treaty we sign today is a firm step toward the true
integration of Latin America,'' Zedillo said, ''an integration that
will always be respectful of the sovereignty and identity of each
nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Also signing were presidents Francisco Flores of El Salvador and
Alfonso Portillo of Guatemala, as well as William Handal,
representing Honduras.
</P>
<P>
   The treaty that takes effect on Jan. 1 includes 124 million
consumers -- three-quarters of them in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiations with the so-called ''Northern Triangle''
countries took eight years. The treaty lifts tariffs on many
agricultural and manufactured goods within 12 years.
</P>
<P>
   Portillo said the treaty was a step toward building the
continent-wide free trade pact that countries in the region have
agreed to seek by 2005.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we all signed with Mexico, why can't we sign among
ourselves?'' Portillo said, referring to Central America's problems
in reaching its own free trade agreements.
</P>
<P>
   The presidents of Costa Rica, Nicaragua and Panama also attended
the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico has had free trade agreements with Nicaragua since 1998
and Costa Rica since 1995, and it is negotiating with Panama.
</P>
<P>
   The trade pact is among several that Zedillo has clinched as he
prepares to leave office in December. A free trade agreement with
the 15-nation European Union takes effect Saturday, and Mexico
recently reached one with Israel. It reached a pact on automobile
trade with Brazil in April.
</P>
<P>
   Excluded from the agreement between Mexico and Central America
are key agricultural goods, including coffee, sugar, bananas and
corn.
</P>
<P>
   It calls for only limited opening in steel and beer, key Mexican
exports, said Eduardo Solis, a Mexican negotiator. Cement is also
excluded.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico will end tariffs on agricultural goods covered by the
agreement within 10 years, while the Central American countries
will have up until 12 years to do so. Mexico will lift tariffs on
manufacturing exports within nine years, while the Central American
nations get up to 11 years.
</P>
<P>
   Two-way trade between Mexico and the three Central American
countries totaled $1.05 billion last year, only 0.4 percent of
Mexico's total trade, according to the Mexican Commerce Ministry.
</P>
<P>
   Two-way trade was $626.2 million with Guatemala, $262.7 million
with El Salvador and $163.7 million with Honduras.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico's drive to expand trade relations reflects an effort to
wean itself from dependence on the United States, which accounted
for 83 percent of total Mexican trade last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-29-00 1815 </TRAILER>
