<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sen. Passes Disclosure Bill  </HEADLINE>
By LAURA MECKLER
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Congress approved the first restrictions on
campaign financing in two decades Thursday, sending President
Clinton legislation that forces tax-exempt political organizations
to reveal who is paying for their campaign-style TV ads, radio
spots and other activities.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton promised to sign the bill, meaning those reports should
be available before this fall's elections.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, approved by an overwhelming majority in the Senate on
Thursday, would leave many interest groups free to continue
broadcasting commercials without naming their donors. And groups
affected by the legislation may reorganize themselves under the tax
laws to avoid disclosure.
</P>
<P>
   But backers argued it was crucial to preserving one of the
pillars of post-Watergate reforms: public disclosure.
</P>
<P>
   ''Today is only the first step,'' said Sen. John McCain,
R-Ariz., who led a bipartisan group of lawmakers as they rolled the
measure past GOP leaders in the House and Senate. ''It is indeed a
great day for democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill only requires disclosure of donations made after it
becomes law. Some backers feared GOP leaders might drag their feet
in sending the bill to the White House, and supporters speculated
that affected groups were now scrambling to raise money before the
bill is signed.
</P>
<P>
   Despite initial opposition from Republican leaders, the
legislation was approved by huge majorities in each chamber of
Congress. It passed the Senate 92-6 Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Even the Senate's fiercest opponent of campaign finance reform
urged his GOP colleagues -- particularly those up for re-election --
to vote yes.
</P>
<P>
   ''I do not think this is a spear worth falling on four months
before an election,'' said Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky.
</P>
<P>
   He noted the legislation only affects groups that organize under
the increasingly popular section 527 of the tax code, which is
reserved for groups created for political purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Other tax-exempt interest groups and companies remain free to
run ads meant to influence elections without disclosing their
donors -- as long as they do not directly advocate a candidate's
election or defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ''When a piece of legislation affects almost nobody, it's easy
to move it rapidly,'' said McConnell.
</P>
<P>
   He was joined by just five others, all Republicans, in voting
no: Sens. Paul Coverdell of Georgia, Jesse Helms of North Carolina,
Connie Mack of Florida and James Inhofe and Don Nickles of
Oklahoma. Sens. Judd Gregg, R-N.H., and Daniel Inouye, D-Hawaii,
did not vote.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation was clearly a win for those who want to overhaul
campaign finance laws, especially for McCain, who built a
presidential bid around his reputation as a campaign finance
reformer although he has yet to see a bill become law.
</P>
<P>
   The last significant change to campaign finance law came in
1979, when disclosure rules were clarified.
</P>
<P>
   ''Passage of this bill proves that public interest can triumph
over special interests,'' Clinton said. Vice President Al Gore and
Texas Gov. George W. Bush also praised the vote.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation requires section 527 groups to notify the
Internal Revenue Service that they exist within 24 hours of
forming. And groups that raise at least $25,000 per year would have
to report contributions of $200 or more and spending of $500 or
more. Reports would be due four times a year, plus immediately
before an election, and should be available before voting this
November.
</P>
<P>
   Reserved for political groups, section 527 has generally been
used by political parties and political action committees. But
while parties and PACs report their contributions and spending to
the Federal Election Commission, a new brand of 527 does not,
claiming to be engaged in ''issues'' not electioneering.
</P>
<P>
   Other interest groups make this distinction as well, though
unlike 527 groups, they face restrictions on their political
activity. The Christian Coalition, for instance, created a 527
group after the IRS clamped down on the organization for its
political activity.
</P>
<P>
   Cleta Mitchell, an attorney who represents several 527 groups,
said she would consider a court challenge to the bill's
constitutionality. In the meantime, she said she would advise her
clients to ''do whatever is necessary to avoid having to report,''
including reorganizing under a different section of tax code.
</P>
<P>
   That didn't stop a little bravado from Sen. Russell Feingold,
D-Wis.: ''We're going to find them,'' he said, ''and we're going to
nail them.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The bill is H.R. 4762.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Congress: http://thomas.loc.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-29-00 1822 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000629.0102 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> American Express president in testimony acknowledges company mistakes </HEADLINE>
By LARRY NEUMEISTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - The president of American Express described
blunders by his company that left it envious of the cozy
relationship its competitors had developed with U.S. banks during
testimony Thursday in the government's case against Visa and
MasterCard.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth I. Chenault, who takes over as the company's chief
executive officer next spring, told how American Express blossomed
after issuing its first charge card in 1958, only to squander its
dominant position later.
</P>
<P>
   He is a key government witness in a civil case in which the
Justice Department seeks to prove that Visa and MasterCard violated
antitrust laws by joining with banks to create rules that block the
banks from doing business with American Express and Discover.
</P>
<P>
   The government wants U.S. District Judge Barbara S. Jones in
Manhattan to prevent some of the nation's largest banks from
continuing to unduly influence the two credit card networks, thus
stifling competition. The government also wants to eliminate the
rule that prevents banks offering Visa and MasterCard from issuing
other credit cards.
</P>
<P>
   Visa International, based in Foster City, Calif., and MasterCard
International Inc., headquartered in Purchase, N.Y., are nonprofit
associations made up of some 8,500 banks. Together they control
about three-fourths of the bank credit card market in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   CardWeb.com, which studies the industry, said that as of the end
of 1999, Visa had a 49 percent market share, while MasterCard had
about 28 percent. American Express Co., headquartered in New York,
had a 17 percent share, while Discover, which is owned by the New
York-based Morgan Stanley Dean Witter &AMP; Co. brokerage firm, has 6
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Chenault testified that Visa and MasterCard as early as 1981
mounted an effective public relations campaign to convince the
nation's banks that American Express was competing against the
banks for bank customers.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're going to steal your customers,'' he said the banks
were told.
</P>
<P>
   The lingering suspicions about American Express' intentions,
along with a lucrative relationship between the banks and the Visa
and MasterCard networks, made it difficult to persuade banks to
promote American Express products, Chenault said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Banks were not actively pushing our products,'' he said. ''It
became very clear to me that the partnership with banks was
incredibly powerful.''
</P>
<P>
   Chenault, though, blamed American Express executives for making
poor decisions in the last two decades which, he said, held the
company back as competitors surged ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were losing relevance with our customers,'' he said at one
point. ''We were trying to be all things to all people with a few
products.''
</P>
<P>
   He said American Express in the early 1990s needed to
aggressively expand the number of merchants who accepted the card
but did not realize how out of favor it had fallen.
</P>
<P>
   ''If I needed a wake-up call, it would be called the Boston Fee
Party,'' he said of the decision by some Boston restaurant owners
to boycott the card because they believed American Express charged
them too much per transaction.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, American Express analyzed its fees and restructured
them, lowering them in some markets, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said his company's rejection of an opportunity to team up
with American Airlines was a ''big, big mistake,'' especially since
so many American Express customers were business people who
traveled a lot.
</P>
<P>
   ''We in fact did not understand that this was a terrific valve
for our core customers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Then American Express did not aggressively attempt to team up
with AT&AMP;T when the company wanted to offer its own charge card with
no fee.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a mistake for us not to be more aggressive,'' he said.
''The free-for-life offer sent shock waves through the credit card
industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Chenault said he remains convinced that American Express
ultimately must forge good relationships with banks and continue to
sign up merchants who accept the card.
</P>
<P>
   On cross examination, he conceded that American Express had
missed some opportunities over the years because of its own
arrogance.
</P>
<P>
   ''Volume would give us lower costs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Noah Hanft, deputy general counsel for MasterCard, said there
was nothing in Chenault's testimony to indicate that consumers were
being harmed or that competition was hindered by the Visa and
MasterCard networks.
</P>
<P>
   Chenault, he said, ''testified that, in the past, Amex made bad
business decisions that significantly affected their ability to
compete in the marketplace and that their desire to work with banks
was part of their attempt to compensate for these mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly Presta, vice president of Visa USA, said it showed that
American Express ''would rather whine in court than compete in the
marketplace.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that although Discover was a younger company, it had
used mail and phone promotions to put more cards in the market than
American Express, which ''proves that competition in the payment
card industry is rampant.''
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.visa.com
</P>
<P>
   http://www.mastercard.com
</P>
<P>
   http://www.americanexpress.com
</P>
<P>
   Department of Justice: http://www.usdoj.gov/atr/cases/indx57.htm
</P>
