<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hospital and DYFS accused of discriminating against HIV-positive mother </HEADLINE>
By JEFFREY GOLD
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) - A lawsuit charges that a pregnant woman
whose blood was tested for the virus that causes AIDS without her
consent later had her newborn taken from her by state officials who
filed false documents after she refused to give an anti-AIDS drug
to the child.
</P>
<P>
   The child was ultimately returned, said Lenora Lapidus, legal
director for the state chapter of the American Civil Liberties
Union.
</P>
<P>
   A Trenton hospital and the state Division of Youth and Family
Services are defendants in the lawsuit, filed in U.S. District
Court here Wednesday on behalf of ''Jane Doe'' of Mercer County by
the Women and AIDS Clinic at Rutgers Law School and the ACLU.
</P>
<P>
   DYFS spokesman Andy Williams said the agency cannot comment
because it had not seen the lawsuit, and also because it cannot
discuss specific families.
</P>
<P>
   In general, he said, the agency acts upon referrals. HIV
exposure alone is not a reason to remove a child, or to become
involved with a family, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''There would have to be some sense that the child's health or
safety is involved,'' Williams said. ''The standard of removal
should always be the safety of the child.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the hospital, Capital Health System's Mercer
Campus, could not comment on the lawsuit because they had not yet
been seen the complaint, and also because they did not know who the
woman was since she was not named, said spokeswoman Luann McCarty.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about hospital policy, McCarty said, ''We do not release
any information without the patient's consent. The only exceptions
would be if we are required to do so by court order, statute, or if
a regulation mandates us to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinic lawyer Cynthia M. Dennis said the state AIDS Assistance
Act does have exceptions, ''but we're alleging that there was an
unlawful breach of confidentiality in this instance.''
</P>
<P>
   In essence, the information went to someone who should not have
received it, Dennis said.
</P>
<P>
   The mother went to the hospital in July 1998 and was tested for
HIV without her consent, in violation of the law, the lawsuit said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Just because a woman is pregnant doesn't mean she loses that
right,'' Lapidus said.
</P>
<P>
   She tested positive, and the information was given to DYFS,
violating her confidentiality, Lapidus said.
</P>
<P>
   The mother refused to give the child AZT, an anti-AIDS drug,
which was recommended ''based solely on the mother's HIV test,''
Lapidus said.
</P>
<P>
   To support its efforts to remove the child, DYFS filed false
affidavits stating that the woman was involved with drugs at the
time of her pregnancy, the lawsuit said.
</P>
<P>
   The baby was out of the mother's custody for about 20 days,
Dennis said.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis and Lapidus declined to disclose the mother's town or the
child's HIV status or gender.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit seeks unspecified money damages.
</P>
<P>
   Capital Health System's Mercer Campus was formerly known as the
Mercer Medical Center. Capital Health was formed at the end of 1997
by the merger of Mercer Medical Center and Helene Fuld Medical
Center, which is also in Trenton.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.aclu.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-29-00 1836 </TRAILER>
