<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 18:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> White House May Delay Execution  </HEADLINE>
By DEB RIECHMANN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The White House suggested Thursday that it
would hold up the Aug. 5 execution of a federal inmate -- the first
since 1963 -- if the Justice Department isn't able to finish
updating clemency guidelines for federal death row prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   ''I certainly know that the clemency issue is something that has
to be completed before we would move forward on the -- on any
federal execution,'' White House press secretary Joe Lockhart said.
''Obviously the guidelines have to be there -- there has to be a
procedure for an inmate on the equivalent of federal death row to
apply for clemency.''
</P>
<P>
   Until ''the process is complete, there won't be'' an execution,
Lockhart added.
</P>
<P>
   He said the clemency rules ''are almost complete'' but that it
is unclear whether the process, which includes a period of public
comment, would be finished by Aug. 5.
</P>
<P>
   On May 26, U.S. District Judge Filemon Vela set an Aug. 5
execution date for convicted killer Juan Raul Garza, ordering the
43-year-old inmate to be executed by injection at 6 a.m. in the
federal death chamber in Terre Haute, Ind.
</P>
<P>
   The Bureau of Prisons and Justice Department officials wanted
the court to delay scheduling the execution until they could finish
reviewing the draft of a detailed technical manual about the manner
of conducting the execution, including rules for last-minute
clemency appeals.
</P>
<P>
   But the judge set execution date anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Legally, there are at least three ways the government could stop
or delay the execution: Government lawyers could persuade a federal
appeals court to delay the execution. President Clinton could
commute Garza's sentence to less than death. Or the president could
grant Garza a temporary reprieve while his case or his appeal for
clemency is further considered.
</P>
<P>
   The last reprieve was granted in 1937 by President Franklin D.
Roosevelt. Typically, reprieves merely postpone the sentence for 30
days.
</P>
<P>
   Garza was convicted in Brownsville, Texas, in August 1993 for
killing three men between April 1990 and January 1991. A 10-count
indictment named him as the boss of a drug ring that imported tons
of marijuana into the United States between 1983 and 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Garza told a reporter for The Associated Press in 1994: ''I
didn't kill any of these people. ... I got the shaft.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-29-00 1845 </TRAILER>
