<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Would Veto Bankruptcy Bill  </HEADLINE>
By MARCY GORDON
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- For the second time this month, President
Clinton threatened Thursday to veto legislation rewriting the
bankruptcy laws that he contends is unfair to ordinary debtors.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to congressional leaders, Clinton said he believes
the legislation, which lawmakers have been tinkering with for weeks
behind closed doors, still lacks the needed balance of protecting
deserving debtors while also stemming abuses of the bankruptcy
system.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would like to sign a balanced consumer bankruptcy bill that
would encourage responsibility and reduce abuses of the bankruptcy
system on the part of debtors and creditors alike,'' he wrote. ''We
can target the abuses without placing unnecessary barriers before
those in need of a fresh start who turn to bankruptcy as a last
resort.''
</P>
<P>
   The House and Senate have passed differing versions of the
legislation, which would make it harder for people to sweep away
their debts in bankruptcy proceedings. Both bills cleared with
veto-proof margins, but reconciling the differences between the
two, for a final vote by the two chambers, has been an arduous task
for lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said their negotiations have produced a measure that
''has lost some of the balance that the Senate bill had tried to
achieve, albeit imperfectly.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I will veto the bill that we understand the Republicans plan
to forward to my desk. But I continue to urge Congress to
reconsider and send me a fair bill that meets the test of
balance,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Charles Grassley, R-Iowa, a chief sponsor of the
legislation, called Clinton's letter an ''obstructionist tactic.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're going to continue putting the best legislation together
that we can because there is such broad, bipartisan support for
reforming the system,'' Grassley said. ''In fact, the level of
support is so strong, when the dust settles, the White House might
conclude that a veto would be unwise.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Paul Wellstone, D-Minn., who has used his senatorial
power to hold up the bankruptcy legislation, said the renewed veto
threat will strengthen its opponents in Congress. ''I look forward
to working with the president to defeat it,'' he said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation would apply new standards for determining
whether people filing for bankruptcy should be forced to repay
their debts under a court-approved reorganization plan instead of
having them dissolved.
</P>
<P>
   It has been pushed by banks, credit card companies and other
consumer-credit businesses, but has raised protests recently from
consumer advocates, unions, women's groups and religious leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton renewed his objection to a provision that would exempt
debt collectors from current law prohibiting harassment of debtors
if they are trying to collect on bounced checks that have been
outstanding for 30 days or more. Creditors would be allowed to use
tactics such as late-night telephone calls to debtors and repeated
dunning over the phone.
</P>
<P>
   The president said he also was concerned that the legislation
doesn't adequately crack down on wealthy debtors who use homestead
exemptions in some states to shield their assets from creditors in
bankruptcy proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is unfair to leave this loophole for the wealthy in
place,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   And Clinton said he was disturbed by ''inadequate'' language in
a provision that would prohibit people found to have violated laws
protecting abortion clinics from using bankruptcy proceedings to
escape fines and civil judgments.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-29-00 1851 </TRAILER>
