<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 18:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Traficant Plans To Back Republican  </HEADLINE>
By KATHERINE RIZZO
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP)-- Democratic Rep. Jim Traficant of Ohio said
Thursday he'll break ranks and vote to keep a Republican, Rep.
Dennis Hastert, as speaker of the House next year -- a pledge that
complicates his own party's bid to gain control in the fall
elections.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview on the nationally syndicated ''Hannity &AMP;
Colmes'' radio program, the maverick eight-term Democrat said
''Hastert's a good man and I'm going to vote for for him for
speaker and I don't give a damn who knows it.''
</P>
<P>
   The vote for speaker is the first major roll call taken when a
new Congress convenes in January. The party that wins that vote
controls the flow of legislation to the floor for the next two
years and appoints chairmen of all committees and subcommittees.
</P>
<P>
   If Traficant follows through, Democrats would have to win seven
seats in November; right now, they're only six seats behind.
</P>
<P>
   House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt's office had no comment
about Traficant's remark. If Democrats gain a majority of House
seats, Gephardt would be in line to become speaker.
</P>
<P>
   Traficant's statement came a day after Hastert, an Illinois
congressman, signed off on a huge plum for the Democrat from
Poland, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert agreed to allow some $30 million to be earmarked in a
supplemental appropriations bill for a convention center project in
Youngstown.
</P>
<P>
   The entire kitty for lawmakers' special projects in that bill
was roughly $100 million, and it was viewed as part of the
courtship of Traficant that Hastert allotted such a large portion
of it to a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   But Traficant is no ordinary Democrat. He has been flirting with
party-switching for years, negotiating what he can for his Rust
Belt district and keeping leaders of both parties guessing. He also
has a record of getting bills and amendments through Republican-led
committees.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Traficant did something unthinkable for any
other Democrat. While other members of his party were salivating at
the prospect of being able to run campaign ads blasting Republicans
for refusing to raise the minimum wage, Traficant went to a
GOP-only meeting and advised Republicans to support a minimum wage
bill lest they lose the House majority.
</P>
<P>
   Traficant doesn't participate in many events with his fellow
Ohio lawmakers, but has many good one-on-one relationships. During
his primary battle this spring, three Republican colleagues signed
a letter supporting him.
</P>
<P>
   Traficant later complained that officials of his own party sided
against him in that primary. Democratic leaders denied it.
</P>
<P>
   ''He believes, and I think rightly so, that the leadership of
his party hung him out to dry in his recently concluded primary,''
March 7, said Rep. Steve LaTourette, R-0hio.
</P>
<P>
   Traficant is approaching the end of his eighth term in the House
amid uncertainty over his future. He has always been a popular
political figure in eastern Ohio's 17th Congressional District, but
a series of federal subpoenas has led him to declare that he
expects to be indicted as part of a wide-ranging Youngstown
corruption probe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
