<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 19:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Oarsman Tries Pacific Cross  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru (AP) -- A flotilla of local fisherman from the
southern coastal town of Ilo paddled alongside British rower Jim
Shekhdar on Thursday as he embarked on a solo voyage across the
Pacific to Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Shekhdar, 53, plans to cross 8,500 miles of ocean in an odyssey
that he hopes will take less than six months.
</P>
<P>
   ''I feel apprehensive and anxious to go,'' he told The
Associated Press by phone before climbing into his
technology-packed, 23-foot boat, the Le Shark. ''I just want to do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   If successful, Shekhdar will claim the longest, coast-to-coast
solo crossing of the Pacific on record, according to the
London-based Ocean Rowing society.
</P>
<P>
   In December 1997, the management consultant for the European
Union completed a 3,013-mile, two-man rowing voyage across the
Atlantic Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   This journey comes nearly three months after another British
oarsman and a French rower each had to be rescued during similar
solo crossing attempts of the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   In early April, a Coast Guard plane reached Andrew Halsey about
1,200 miles southeast of Hawaii. That rescue came three days after
French rower Jo Le Guen was retrieved one-third of the way into his
attempted 5,580-mile Pacific crossing. Eight of his toes had to be
amputated.
</P>
<P>
   Shekhdar said he's carrying an eight-month supply of food,
satellite positioning equipment, communications devices, and a
satellite phone to keep in contact with his wife and two daughters
in England.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-29-00 1903 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000629.0110 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 19:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Youth Is Served at NBA Draft  </HEADLINE>
By CHRIS SHERIDAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Darius Miles and Quentin Richardson had
ditched their expensive suits for T-shirts by the early morning
hours Thursday as they walked together along the downtown streets.
</P>
<P>
   The two youngsters already have shared an apartment in Chicago,
and they'll be seeing a lot more of each other in the years ahead
as teammates with the Los Angeles Clippers -- the team that emerged
as the big winner in the NBA draft.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everybody always gets a chance to start over. This here is a
golden opportunity for a lot of young guys,'' Richardson said,
''and we'll get a chance to go in there and start something
sweet.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers acquired Miles, Richardson, Corey Maggette, Derek
Strong and Keyon Dooling through the draft and trades to restock a
roster that has gone through annual defections, as the low-rent
franchise remained mired in a losing mode.
</P>
<P>
   But things should be different next season for the Clippers, who
suddenly are a lot better and a lot younger.
</P>
<P>
   Miles is 18, and Richardson, Maggette and Dooling, a point guard
from Missouri whom the Clippers acquired from Orlando, are all 20.
Theirs were some of the baby faces on display during a draft night
that furthered the trend of the NBA getting younger and younger.
</P>
<P>
   After senior Kenyon Martin of Cincinnati was selected first, the
next 10 picks were underclassmen. In all, 19 first-rounders were
underclassmen or high school players, breaking the record of 17 set
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ''The game's getting younger and younger,'' said Michigan's
Jamal Crawford, who played less than one full year with the
Wolverines and was taken by the Cavaliers at No. 8, then traded to
the Bulls for Texas junior Chris Mihm, the seventh pick.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it will continue to get that way,'' Crawford said.
</P>
<P>
   Even the staid, old Utah Jazz got in on the act, drafting high
schooler DeShawn Stevenson of Fresno, Calif., who got into a brawl
involving 20 youths at a gymnasium shortly after he was drafted.
</P>
<P>
   Joaquin Lopez, a school custodian who saw the fight, said
Stevenson was jumped.
</P>
<P>
   ''He got punched and then landed some punches of his own,'' he
said. ''Then four of them chased (Stevenson) up in the stands and
beat on him before he got away.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevenson was escorted to his new Lexus SUV as some of the
combatants gave chase.
</P>
<P>
   Stevenson, 19, will have a chance to take over the shooting
guard spot being vacated in Utah by Jeff Hornacek. Stevenson's
competition for the spot will come from second-year pro Quincy
Lewis, perhaps the most babyfaced player in the NBA, who was
coincidentally in attendance Wednesday night at the draft.
</P>
<P>
   Besides taking Stevenson with the 23rd pick, Utah holds rights
to 6-9 Russian forward Andrei Kirilenko, a skinny 19-year-old
drafted in the first round last year.
</P>
<P>
   ''We haven't usually taken these gambles,'' coach Jerry Sloan
said. ''We've always tried to be a little more secure, but we're in
a position now where the structure of our team has changed almost
completely for what it's going to be down the line.''
</P>
<P>
   Another team making a bold move -- or a series of them -- was the
Orlando Magic.
</P>
<P>
   Orlando jettisoned two of its three lottery picks, along with
Maggette and Strong, to position the team $21 million under the
salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   Orlando can now go out and sign two maximum-salaried free agents
from a list that includes Tim Duncan, Grant Hill, Eddie Jones,
Tracy McGrady and Jalen Rose. Teams can begin negotiating with free
agents Saturday but can't sign them until Aug. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Without the extra cap room, the Magic would have been forced to
try to work out a sign-and-trade deal with one of the teams that
will be losing one of their stars.
</P>
<P>
   ''We might have been able to sign two free agents before, but
the sign-and-trade thing would have come into play. It would have
been tougher,'' Magic coach Doc Rivers said. ''We have the money
now to go out and get it done.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
