<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Packer Craig Newsome Arrested  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LA CROSSE, Wis. (AP) -- Former NFL cornerback Craig Newsome was
charged Thursday with using a false drug prescription to obtain a
painkiller.
</P>
<P>
   Newsome, 28, who has been coaching the La Crosse River Rats of
the Indoor Football League, was charged with one count of obtaining
a controlled substance by fraud, a felony that carries a maximum
six years in prison and a $30,000 fine upon conviction
</P>
<P>
   ''He went to a pharmacy with a prescription in the name of
another individual. He gave it to them and got the drug, Lortab,''
La Crosse County Assistant District Attorney Todd Bjerke said.
</P>
<P>
   The prescription was for 100 tablets of Lortab, and a Shopko
pharmacist filled it Sunday before becoming suspicious and
contacting Newsome's doctor, who said he did not recognize the
woman's name and never wrote a prescription for her, the criminal
complaint said.
</P>
<P>
   A police search of Newsome's La Crosse apartment Wednesday found
''various prescription drugs,'' some of which had been prescribed
for Newsome and his wife but some that were in the name of another
person, the complaint said.
</P>
<P>
   ''While the charge against Mr. Newsome is serious, it alleges
that he improperly obtained a prescription medicine often used to
treat severe pain,'' said James Kroner, Newsome's attorney. ''This
case does not have anything to do with the use or distribution of
illicit drugs. Calling this a drug bust as some in the press have
done is misleading and unfair.''
</P>
<P>
   Kroner declined further comment.
</P>
<P>
   Newsome, who spent last season with San Francisco after four
years with Green Bay, was released from the La Crosse County Jail
on Wednesday night after posting $5,000 bond, said sheriff's Sgt.
Steven Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   Circuit Judge Michael Mulroy set July 27 for a status hearing,
Bjerke said.
</P>
<P>
   River Rats general manager Lee Snapp said Thursday that Newsome
has been ''relieved of his duties'' as coach. Snapp said offensive
coordinator John Schimon will serve as coach for the River Rats'
remaining game July 1.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are concerned about his family and his future and are
hoping everything works out for him,'' Snapp said.
</P>
<P>
   There was no telephone listing for Newsome in the La Crosse area
when The Associated Press tried to reach him for comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
