<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 19:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Assembly postpones vote on massive school construction bill  </HEADLINE>
By KATHLEEN CANNON
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - New Jersey schools will have to wait a
little longer for state funds to pay for new or renovated
facilities.
</P>
<P>
   While the state Senate on Thursday approved a multibillion
dollar school construction bill that includes last minute changes
made by Gov. Christie Whitman, the Assembly postponed scheduled
action.
</P>
<P>
   Assembly Speaker Jack Collins complained earlier in the day that
his members had no time to read Whitman's changes, which were
delivered late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But senators, who received the governor's suggested changes at
the same time as the Assembly, needed no extra time. They voted
38-0 to accept the new version and send it back to the Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, which includes $6 billion for the state's 30
so-called special needs districts and $2.6 billion for all other
New Jersey schools, is now scheduled for Assembly action July 13.
</P>
<P>
   Once signed, the bill is designed to satisfy a state Supreme
Court order that the state provide full funding to repair or
replace crumbling schools in the special needs districts. But the
state has already missed the court's ''spring 2000'' deadline for
new construction projects to commence.
</P>
<P>
   Under the measure, districts will receive a minimum 40 percent
state grant for their construction projects, with the poorest
schools receiving 100 percent funding.
</P>
<P>
   State borrowing would be capped at $8.6 billion, although
lawmakers could appropriate more if they need to.
</P>
<P>
   But to the dismay of some Assembly Republicans, Whitman stripped
the Legislature of any veto power over individual school projects,
a change endorsed by the Senate Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   This and other changes were part of Whitman's conditional veto
of the original bill, which previously passed both houses.
</P>
<P>
   ''The program must be legally sufficient so that it meets
constitutional requirements,'' Whitman said in her veto message to
lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   She also expressed concerns about the cost of the program.
</P>
<P>
   ''If costs are permitted to expand beyond what is fiscally
sound, the program will become unsustainable, benefitting no one,''
her message said.
</P>
<P>
   To control costs, the governor included construction ''soft
costs'' such as design work and site acquisition in a set $138 per
square foot allowance that the state will fund. These costs were
previously outside the allowance.
</P>
<P>
   Other changes among the myriad in her 52-page veto message
included adding preschool construction costs to the program, and
allowing community development projects around new schools in six
cities.
</P>
<P>
   Collins told reporters his members did not feel ''comfortable''
voting on such a comprehensive set of changes soon after being
briefed on them.
</P>
<P>
   ''The problem is, my members just walked in 40 minutes ago, and
I don't think they're ready to vote on the state's largest building
project,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think people want us to make sure we do it right,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The speaker predicted that the bill will eventually pass, but he
declined to say whether he will support it. He said he was
particularly concerned about the decision to deny him oversight of
the projects.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think any time the Legislature is denied powers that are
rightfully theirs, that rankles me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Whitman spokesman Peter McDonough said Collins is expecting
too much. The Supreme Court would not allow legislative tinkering
with the mandatory full funding for the poor districts, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Look at the court order. It's pretty clear that the districts
need to be funded at 100 percent. Putting roadblocks in the way is
probably a violation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. William Gormley, R-Atlantic, who sponsored the bill in the
Senate, said he was not concerned that the Assembly was delaying
final passage past the court deadline.
</P>
<P>
   He sidestepped questions about whether Collins may be playing
political games with Senate President Donald DiFrancesco. Both the
Assembly speaker and the Senate president are likely 2001
gubernatorial candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ''My understanding is, he's calling the Assembly back into
session. That sounds like good faith to me,'' Gormley said. ''The
best jockeying is to get the bill passed.''
</P>
<P>
   DiFrancesco confessed he did not know what Collins was up to. He
also said he does not fear that the bill may be derailed in the
Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   A two week delay ''should not make a difference to the passage
or implementation of the bill,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-29-00 1922 </TRAILER>
