<HEADLINE> Senate OKs Family Care health insurance program  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - The state Senate on Thursday approved a
bill to bring health insurance coverage to 125,000 low-income and
working families.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, S-1467, passed by a 39-0 vote and now goes to the desk
of Gov. Christie Whitman, who made Family Care one of her
priorities for the year.
</P>
<P>
   The program would provide subsidized health insurance for
working New Jersey residents.
</P>
<P>
   To qualify, applicants must be a parent or child caretaker whose
family income does not exceed 200 percent of the federal poverty
level, or a single adult or childless couple whose income does not
exceed 100 percent of the poverty level.
</P>
<P>
   Although KidCare, the children's insurance program, was slow to
get started in 1998, it has since built enrollment of children to
more than 60,000.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, officials have more robust forecasts for quick
enrollment in Family Care because many of the KidCare families are
already screened and qualified to enroll in the larger program.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman's $21.5 billion budget for the new fiscal year includes
$80 million for Family Care, with additional funding drawn from
federal matching funds and the state's share of the national
tobacco settlement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
