<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 19:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ugandans Rally For Political Future  </HEADLINE>
By HRVOJE HRANJSKI
<TEXT>
<P>
   KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) -- A referendum to gauge support for a
political system credited with creating stability but criticized as
undemocratic drew a reportedly light voter turnout Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The nonbinding ballot question asked voters whether they
supported President Yoweri Museveni's National Resistance Movement
or wanted a multiparty system. Traditional political parties,
allowed to exist in name only, called for a boycott of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   In his first public comment on the vote, Museveni said Thursday
if his Movement received less than 60 percent of the vote, he would
consider changing Uganda's political system.
</P>
<P>
   ''If there are no problems in the organization of the elections
or natural causes like rain preventing all the registered voters
from casting their ballots, and the Movement gets less than 60
percent, I will know there is a serious problem with the Movement
system,'' Museveni told the Integral Regional Information Network,
a U.N. information service.
</P>
<P>
   ''But we shall make a judgment after looking at the results and
the voter turnout,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The private Central Broadcasting Station radio reported a
generally low turnout nationwide. Some polling stations in Kampala
said only half the registered voters on their lists had turned up.
</P>
<P>
   The 16,500 polling stations closed at 5 p.m., and vote counting
got under way immediately. Results are to be announced by Saturday.
The Electoral Commission said 9.6 million voters had registered in
the country of 22 million.
</P>
<P>
   News media reported a higher turnout in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
   In northern Uganda, where an estimated 700,000 people have been
displaced by a long-running rebellion, the turnout was reported to
be extremely low.
</P>
<P>
   There seemed little doubt, however, that most Ugandans are
likely to stick with Museveni's Movement, credited for the longest
period of peace and economic prosperity since Uganda's independence
from Britain in 1963.
</P>
<P>
   In groups of 10 and 20, voters lined up under intermittent rain
at churches, schools and hospitals in Kampala, to pick out their
names on long lists, then take a ballot and circle the yellow bus
to show they favored the Movement or the sky-blue dove to
demonstrate their wish to return to a multiparty system.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're not mature yet for the multipartyism,'' said a
45-year-old civil servant who asked not to be named as he cast his
ballot in favor of Museveni's National Resistance Movement. ''I'm
not so young not to remember what the past was like.''
</P>
<P>
   The memory of Uganda's recent, bloody history would seem to play
in the Movement's -- and Museveni's -- favor.
</P>
<P>
   In 1971, Idi Amin ousted the corrupt, repressive regime of
President Milton Obote. But things fell apart for Amin after he
expelled more than 70,000 people of Indian background who were the
country's economic mainstay.
</P>
<P>
   Amin's forces killed at least 200,000 people and were only
stopped by the intervention in 1979 of the Tanzanian army -- and
Ugandan exiles including Museveni. They restored Obote to power in
what turned out to be nearly another decade of chaos and terror
that ended only when Museveni and his movement won a five-year bush
war in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years later, Museveni was elected president over two other
candidates and has presided over a remarkable transformation of the
economy and an overall improvement in human rights and press
freedom.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-29-00 1939 </TRAILER>
