<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Conectiv may build power plant on site of Roebling factory  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   FLORENCE, N.J. (AP) - Conectiv, the state's third-largest
utility, said earlier this month it is considering building a $300
million power plant on the site of the abandoned John A. Roebling
Steel Works.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the Delaware-based utility presented the Florence
Township Redevelopment Agency with preliminary plans to build two
gas-fired power plants on the 200-acre site.
</P>
<P>
   The Roebling factory has been empty since 1982. It was declared
a federal Superfund site in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Conectiv, which serves 473,000 customers in eight southern New
Jersey counties, said it wants to build two 500-megawatt plants on
about 75 acres. A third of those acres would serve as a buffer.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Kennedy, a spokeswoman for Conectiv, said Thursday that
the utility presented a proposal with the flexibility to build a
second plant on the site. The company's immediate plans call for
one combustion turbine generating station to be built, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Conectiv is looking at several locations from New Jersey to
Virginia, but it hasn't picked one yet. Roebling is a favorable
prospect, she said, because of its proximity to the Delaware River
for cooling and nearby railways for fuel delivery.
</P>
<P>
   The utility needs township officials to sign a letter of intent
before it can proceed with preliminary studies.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's announcement was met with displeasure from residents
who wanted restaurants and retail shops to be built there.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was shocked,'' resident Marlyn Argast told The Courier-Post
of Cherry Hill. ''I don't think we're going to be able to do the
kinds of things at this site we had hoped to do, like put
restaurants in. You know no one is going to want to have dinner
where a plant is going to be.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm trying to keep an open mind,'' said planning board member
Colleen Carney. ''But I think It's going to be a hard sell.''
</P>
<P>
   Conectiv should make a final decision by the end of the year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
