<HEADLINE> Two physicians indicted in sexual assaults on European tourists  </HEADLINE>
By SAMUEL MAULL
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - A Manhattan physician has been indicted on
charges of drugging and sodomizing two female European tourists and
second doctor has been indicted for allegedly hindering the
prosecution of the first.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Selim Can Alkoc, 29, a psychiatry resident at St.
Luke's-Roosevelt Hospital, met the 21-year-old women in Canada and
invited them to his West 59th Street apartment where, on May 23, he
allegedly drugged, raped and sodomized them, said Barbara Thompson
of the Manhattan district attorney's office.
</P>
<P>
   Later that day, said Thompson, the women filed complaints
against Alkoc. Medical exams showed that the women, both
Scandinavian, had been physically injured in ways consistent with
sexual assault.
</P>
<P>
   On June 7, a Manhattan grand jury indicted Alkoc on charges of
rape, sodomy, sexual abuse and assault, Thompson said. She said
Alkoc fled to his native Turkey before he was arrested or indicted.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a St. Luke's-Roosevelt anesthesiology resident, Dr.
Turker Sengul, 28, was indicted on charges of hindering prosecution
and tampering with evidence, Thompson said.
</P>
<P>
   She said Sengul, who lived in the same hospital-subsidized
building as Alkoc, helped his colleague and countryman collect
mail, get clothing from his apartment and even carried Alkoc's
pager to mislead police.
</P>
<P>
   A court complaint says Sengul admitted to a prosecutor that the
day after Alkoc was indicted, he went to Alkoc's apartment to
remove several videotapes hidden under a bed and in a vacuum
cleaner.
</P>
<P>
   The court complaint says Sengul also admitted that, at Alkoc's
direction, he took video equipment and a computer from the
apartment. A law enforcement source who spoke on condition of
anonymity said the tapes show Alkoc in sexual encounters with other
women who appeared to be drugged.
</P>
<P>
   Sengul was arrested June 15 and released on $20,000 bail. After
his arraignment Thursday, he was jailed without bail pending a
hearing Friday. Prosecutors said they feared he, too, might flee to
Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   But Alkoc's lawyer, Brian Perskin, said his client had not fled.
He said Alkoc had not been charged with anything two weeks after
the Swedish women complained to police, so he moved back to Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   Perskin said he believes extraditing Alkoc will be difficult if
not impossible because he is a Turkish national.
</P>
<P>
   Sengul's lawyer, Al Brackley, could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Mandler, spokesman for St. Luke's-Roosevelt, said Alkoc and
Sengul were suspended without pay pending the outcome of the
investigation. Meanwhile, he said, the hospital is cooperating with
the authorities.
</P>
<P>
   The top charges against Alkoc, rape and sodomy in the first
degree, are punishable by up to 25 years in prison. The charges
against Sengul - hindering prosecution and tampering with evidence
- carry prison terms of up to four years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-29-00 1944 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
