<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fiji Moves To Isolate Hostage-Takers  </HEADLINE>
By STEVEN GUTKIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUVA, Fiji (AP) -- Gunmen holding 27 Fijian lawmakers hostage
briefly detained 16 journalists Thursday after the army spoke of
plans to cut water, electricity and telephone lines to the besieged
compound
</P>
<P>
   Guards armed with machine guns stopped the journalists from
leaving the parliamentary compound where the government hostages,
including deposed Prime Minister Mahendra Chaudhry, are being held.
</P>
<P>
   An hour later, the journalists were released, but the incident
has raised fears the gunmen might try to take more hostages in the
government crisis now in its sixth week in the Pacific island
nation.
</P>
<P>
   ''It actually marks a dangerous escalation in this business,''
said Michael Field, a reporter for Agence France-Presse who was
among those held. Nine of the detained journalists were from
abroad.
</P>
<P>
   The incident followed an announcement by Fiji's military rulers
that they planned to cordon off Parliament to isolate and cut off
supplies to the hostage-takers.
</P>
<P>
   ''People moving freely at any moment will have to be stopped,
media will have to be stopped,'' army spokesman Lt. Col. Filipo
Tarakinikini told Fiji TV. He said officials were considering
cutting water, electricity, and telephone lines to the gunmen.
</P>
<P>
   By Thursday evening, there was no evidence that any of the
measures had been put into effect.
</P>
<P>
   Before relenting, rebel leader George Speight said it would be
too dangerous for the journalists to go back to their homes and
hotels because of the army presence outside the compound.
</P>
<P>
   The military, which declared martial law 10 days after Speight
and six gunmen stormed Parliament on May 19, had never threatened
journalists.
</P>
<P>
   During Speight's news conference Thursday, he said that if the
parliament compound were cordoned off and supplies cut, the
hostages' safety could be jeopardized because rebel supporters
inside the compound would become ''very angry'' and might harm
them.
</P>
<P>
   When asked whether his supporters might shoot indigenous Fijians
hostages, he replied: ''I would say they would start by shooting
our Indian brothers.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision to cordon the area was to protect citizens'
''security'' and to make sure the rebels take no more captives,
army spokesman Capt. Eroni Volavola told The Associated Press
earlier Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Volavola did not say if isolating the compound was a precursor
to further military action, but it appeared to raise the stakes in
the standoff.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement came a day after Fiji's military rulers said
they will appoint a new civilian government without any input from
the hostage-takers, who have demanded a role in the administration
before releasing their captives.
</P>
<P>
   Speight and his supporters had been involved in selecting new
ministers but were frozen out of the process Wednesday after
refusing to sign an accord that would pave the way for the
immediate release of the hostages.
</P>
<P>
   Tarakinikini said excluding Speight from the negotiations was
''the most pragmatic'' response to the crisis, which had caused
thousands of people to lose their jobs and resulted in ''the whole
country being held for ransom.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the rebels' demands to disenfranchise Fiji's Indians
have been met, including the firing of Chaudhry and the elimination
of the country's 1997 multiracial constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Rebels led by Speight, a former insurance executive, have said
the hostages would die in any attempted rescue. Chaudhry is the
first ethnic Indian to lead Fiji.
</P>
<P>
   Speight, who says he represents the native Fijians, claims
Chaudhry favored Indians at the expense of the indigenous
population.
</P>
<P>
   The standoff has pitted Fiji's poor majority against its
relatively affluent Indian minority, whose ancestors were brought
to Fiji by English colonialists more than a century ago to work in
the country's rich sugar cane fields.
</P>
<P>
   About half the hostages are indigenous Fijian and half are
Indian. On Thursday, the rebels allowed the two groups to see each
other for the first time since they were taken hostage on May 19.
</P>
<P>
   Also Thursday, the U.S. State Department issued a statement
deploring ''both the hostage taking and efforts to deny political
rights to some citizens of Fiji.''
</P>
<P>
   The statement said the United States is ''considering a range of
steps in consultation with other nations that could have a serious
impact on Fiji.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-29-00 1948 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000629.0130 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 19:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Still crazy after all these months: Rocker in NYC  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY McSHANE
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - New York Mets fan Mike Adler had waited since
last October to ask - actually scream - a question for John Rocker.
So when the loudmouth lefty went out to run windsprints Thursday
night, Adler was ready.
</P>
<P>
   ''Why don't you show us respect?'' shouted Adler, proudly
wearing a Mets shirt. He was speaking for his fellow fans, but the
question applied to gays, immigrants, unwed mothers and most other
groups offended by Rocker's insensitive, inane remarks about New
York.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker answered semi-pleasantly, autographed two baseballs, then
issued a public apology. But it did little to lower the level of
bile directed at the man Mets fans, among others, love to despise.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker's apology, shown on Shea's giant screen in left-center
field, was greeted with lusty boos by the crowd. He went out to the
bullpen, with its special protective cover, without incident before
the first pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Rocker had taken a circuitous route to the ballpark.
With a quick wave and dead silence, he backed off his pledge to
mingle with the denizens of the No. 7 subway.
</P>
<P>
   He instead climbed into a black van to meet with representatives
of the players union, who encouraged him to stay off the train. He
returned to his hotel before heading out to Shea Stadium in another
van with tinted windows.
</P>
<P>
   Once safely at the ballpark, he read a brief statement saying
the media has overstated his importance: ''I'm merely a baseball
player guys,'' he said, looking briefly into the cameras.
</P>
<P>
   Disappointed riders of the Queens subway line instead turned out
at the ballpark to greet the pitcher turned poster boy for
insulting comments. One early arrival sported a sign declaring,
''Rocker Is Da Devil.''
</P>
<P>
   ''He's going to get booed, big time,'' warned Darwin Pena, 20,
who exited the subway wearing a No. 7 train T-shirt. ''People in
New York don't like being insulted. He might be dodging
batteries.''
</P>
<P>
   At a sparsely attended anti-Rocker rally beneath the subway,
demonstrators held signs proclaiming ''NYC Says No to RocKKKer''
and the less-imaginative ''Rocker's A Bigot.'' Among the
demonstrators were a half-dozen Queens Little Leaguers.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm going to boo like crazy,'' promised Peter Verry, 17, who
wore a T-shirt with a suggestion that Rocker would undoubtedly
ignore. ''He's shown a lot of disrespect for people and for major
league baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   The fastballer was dubbed ''The Ku Klux Kloser'' after his
racist, homophobic and xenophobic comments in Sports Illustrated
last December. This trip was his first to New York since last
fall's playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Though Rocker had promised to ride the subway to Shea Stadium,
wiser heads (and there are plenty) prevailed on the hurler to
choose a less public form of transportation.
</P>
<P>
   This was a good idea, given that Rocker had redefined political
incorrectness by describing straphangers on the No. 7 line as
''some kid with purple hair ... some queer with AIDS ... some
20-year-old mom with four kids.'' He also complained that New York
has too many foreigners and added: ''How the hell did they get in
this country?''
</P>
<P>
   An assortment of preparations were in place for the Shea return
of reliever Rocker, christened ''Johnny Rotten'' and ''Punk
Rocker'' by the New York tabloids. Despite the city's enmity toward
him, Rocker received the type of security ordinarily reserved for
heads of state.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to police at his hotel, 700 officers were assigned
to Shea instead of the 60 for most games - New York's finest to
protect Atlanta's swinest. There were police on bicycles and
horses, in vans and buses, in uniform and plainclothes.
</P>
<P>
   A limit on beer sales was imposed. A special protective cover
was erected over the Braves' bullpen in left field. During batting
practice, fans were barred from sitting in the first four rows
behind the Braves' dugout.
</P>
<P>
   City Councilman Walter McCaffrey, D-Queens, sent the Braves a
letter asking the team to donate its portion of the gate receipts
to defray the extra security costs. That could add up, since more
than 50,000 fired-up New Yorkers were expected at the game.
</P>
<P>
   There were already hints that the crowd could turn ugly, as some
fans recently handed out fliers on the No. 7 platform advertising
''John Rocker Battery Night.'' Fans were encouraged to bring and
fling their AAs to greet Rocker.
</P>
<P>
   In response, New York Mets officials promised a zero tolerance
policy against fans behaving badly in the stands.
</P>
<P>
   The road trip to hell is just the latest in a series of
self-inflicted woes for Rocker: a suspension for his comments, his
threats against the writer of the SI piece, and a brief demotion to
the minor leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ''Hindsight being 20/20, I would've loved to have missed my
meeting with the Sports Illustrated reporter and I never would've
had to deal with the whole situation,'' Rocker told TBS. ''But then
again, that's the hand I've been dealt and I'll have to make the
best of it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
