<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 19:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawmakers Upset Over Water Rules  </HEADLINE>
By PHILIP BRASHER
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Farm-state lawmakers angry over proposed water
pollution regulations are taking out their frustration on a senior
official at the Agriculture Department.
</P>
<P>
   An amendment added to a USDA spending bill Thursday would cut
off funding, starting Oct. 1, for the office of James Lyons, USDA's
assistant secretary for natural resources. The amendment was
approved on a voice vote.
</P>
<P>
   Lyons' critics say he didn't speak up for farm interests that
oppose a plan by the Environmental Protection Agency to clean up
polluted streams and lakes.
</P>
<P>
   ''Agriculture deserves to have a voice and especially when
regulations are being developed,'' said Rep. Marion Berry, D-Ark.,
who sponsored the amendment. Rep. Saxby Chambliss, R-Ga., said the
amendment would ''send a message'' to the administration that ''we
in Congress are going to continue to work to establish common sense
in this town.''
</P>
<P>
   Lyons did not return a telephone call Thursday. USDA spokesman
Andy Solomon said that Congress ''shouldn't make policy disputes
personal, which is what they appear to be doing in this
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House on Thursday threatened to veto the spending bill
because it doesn't provide as much money as President Clinton
wanted for food safety and other programs. The House will not
finish action on the legislation until July.
</P>
<P>
   In testimony to the House Agriculture Committee on Wednesday,
Lyons conceded that the EPA plan was so unpopular with farm
interests that it had become the ''new four-letter word in rural
America.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposal, which the EPA intends to make final this summer,
would require states to submit plans within 15 years to clean up
every waterway that fails to meet water quality standards.
</P>
<P>
   Landowners would be required to get a pollution discharge permit
if the EPA found they were contributing to nearby water quality
problems and if a state had failed to draft an adequate plan for
improving water quality.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA estimates that there are more than 20,000 streams and
lakes that don't meet water-quality standards.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The bill is H.R. 4461.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: USDA: http://www.usda.gov
</P>
<P>
   EPA: http://www.epa.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
