<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 20:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Schools, other groups mull impact of gay Scout ruling  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - One United Way group in New Jersey has
already cut off funding to the Boy Scouts of America over the youth
organization's rule barring gay troop leaders.
</P>
<P>
   A day after the U.S. Supreme Court ruled 5-4 that
free-association rights allow the Boy Scouts to legally exclude
homosexual Scoutmasters, other United Ways on Thursday were mulling
whether they should end or limit grants to their local Boy Scout
troops.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, officials with groups representing New Jersey school
districts and municipalities were consulting attorneys on the issue
Thursday, but said they expect it will be left up to individual
schools and towns to decide whether they will still let Boy Scout
troops use their facilities.
</P>
<P>
   The Scouts' ''hollow victory'' will cost them support ''because
now the public will see them for what they are, an anti-gay
organization,'' said Lenora Lapidus, legal director of the American
Civil Liberties Union of New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   At the ACLU Lesbian &AMP; Gay Rights Project in New York, director
Matt Coles predicted the Boy Scouts will fade into obscurity within
a few years if they don't change the anti-gay policy. Coles said
schools and government agencies often give Scouts special deals
such as free camping not available to other groups.
</P>
<P>
   ''In states that have passed anti-discrimination laws (such as
New Jersey), the government probably has to stop giving them
sweetheart deals,'' Coles said.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, several officials said, how other groups and
government entities deal with the Boy Scouts' Supreme
Court-sanctioned discrimination - by severing their ties, doing
business as usual or something in between - will be determined in
state courts. They anticipate someone eventually will sue a school
district, for example, for either allowing or barring use of its
public facilities by a Boy Scout group.
</P>
<P>
   ''We wouldn't be surprised to see legal actions by other
groups,'' said Steffanie Bell, a spokeswoman for Gov. Christie
Whitman.
</P>
<P>
   Although the state Attorney General's Office filed a brief with
the Supreme Court supporting the right of Eagle Scout James Dale to
be an assistant scoutmaster in Matawan, Bell said the governor is
not planning to issue any policy statement to guide schools or
municipalities.
</P>
<P>
   It's the same for the New Jersey School Boards Association.
</P>
<P>
   However, spokesman Mike Yaple said the association plans to soon
send the state's 602 school districts an advisory saying that they
could continue renting space to Boy Scouts - and risk being
challenged in court - or adopt a policy on discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   ''If a school board wants to adopt a policy that says it will
not rent to any group that discriminates based on sexual
orientation, they'd be on very solid ground with that,'' Yaple
said.
</P>
<P>
   More than a month before the high court's ruling, United Way of
Somerset County ended 18 months of negotiations with the local Boy
Scout council by deciding to cut off all funding to the group as of
this month, according to president Robert Zdenek.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are now around 10 United Ways around the country that
are no longer affiliated with the Boy Scouts. We're the first in
New Jersey,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have a strong anti-discrimination policy'' requiring all 50
groups that receive funding to agree not to discriminate against
anyone on a number of factors, including sexual orientation, Zdenek
said. ''The Boy Scouts would not sign the policy because of the
sexual orientation provision,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At United Way of Monmouth County, where the Dale case
originated, executive director Jim Bourque said the agency has
already approved a $39,000 allocation to the Scouts for the fiscal
year starting Saturday. He said the agency's board will discuss
what to do at its next meeting in August, when it should have legal
advice from attorneys with United Way of America.
</P>
<P>
   In Camden County, though, where the United Way has allocated
$70,000 to the Boy Scouts for the fiscal year beginning Saturday,
President Mike Moynihan said the board of directors is setting up a
task force to study the situation.
</P>
<P>
   One alternative would be limiting financial support to specific
programs open to everyone, such as the popular school-based
''Learning for Life'' program that teaches at-risk boys and girls
of all ages how to make good decisions in dealing with drugs,
gangs, violence and other problems, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're going to be very careful and do what we feel is best for
the community,'' Moynihan said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-29-00 2007 </TRAILER>
