<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senate OKs final version of highway funding bill, but Assembly balks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - The Senate Thursday approved minor
revisions to a four-year, $3.75 billion program to fund road and
rail projects, but the Assembly postponed a vote for a few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   With a special July session scheduled to deal with school
construction, Assembly Speaker Jack Collins and Democratic minority
leader Joe Doria, D-Hudson, agreed to wait on the Transportation
Trust Fund bill as well.
</P>
<P>
   The Transportation Trust Fund is the major agency that finances
$900 million a year in road and rail projects, and its funding
technically expires at midnight Friday. However, extra money
available from a voter referendum last November and some leftover
funds can keep the Trust Fund solvent for several extra months.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate, Assembly and Whitman administration had been at odds
this spring over the funding and spending in the four-year package.
</P>
<P>
   In previous years, the Trust Fund usually was fueled by a new
funding source like higher gasoline taxes. But this year the main
sponsor, Senate President Donald DiFrancesco, proposed diverting
money out of the existing budget and dedicating it to highways for
the next four years.
</P>
<P>
   Assembly Republicans were concerned about the high spending, and
Whitman was concerned about tying up so much state revenue in
future budget years. Two years ago she had proposed a gasoline tax
increase, but lawmakers scuttled it.
</P>
<P>
   But these issues were resolved in the main bill. The snag
Thursday involved only a minor provision concerning how much
borrowed money could be used to pay for engineering and
professional staff costs in the design of projects.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate on Thursday voted to comply with Whitman's veto
message, but the Assembly, receiving the document late, decided to
wait until July.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Full text of bills available at the Office of Legislative
Services Web site located at http://www.njleg.state.nj.us
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
