<DOCNO> APW20000629.0138 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> School: Arizona Guard Took Money  </HEADLINE>
By ARTHUR H. ROTSTEIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) -- Former University of Arizona All-America
point guard Jason Terry took more than $11,000 and other benefits
from agents after his junior year and as a senior, violating NCAA
rules, school officials said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the university has forfeited its only 1999 NCAA
basketball tournament game and will repay $45,362 to the NCAA, but
will not have to forfeit its regular-season games for 1998-99.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Pacific-10 Conference and the NCAA have accepted and
agreed with the university's self-imposed sanctions, after
completing their own investigations, athletic director Jim
Livengood said. Neither has recommended any additional sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Terry, now with the NBA's Atlanta Hawks, was chosen as a lottery
pick a year ago after being a 1999 first-team AP All-America as a
senior.
</P>
<P>
   He disclosed that he took more than about $4,500 from New York
sports agent Larry Fox after his junior year, Livengood said. Terry
also received about $7,000 from Ndidi Opia, a San Francisco agent,
while a senior, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Livengood said the violations made Terry ineligible for his
entire senior year.
</P>
<P>
   The university has forfeited its first-round, 61-60 NCAA
tournament loss to Oklahoma, and will pay back a 45 percent share
of its tournament television revenue, under NCAA requirements.
</P>
<P>
   But because a Pac-10 review found no evidence the university
knew about Terry's violations until afterward, forfeiture of the
entire 1998-99 schedule will not be necessary. It had initially
intended to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Terry has agreed to reimburse the university for the money to be
repaid to the NCAA, Livengood said.
</P>
<P>
   Telephone listings for Terry, Fox and Opia could not immediately
be found.
</P>
<P>
   Wildcats coach Lute Olson said he talked earlier this month with
Terry, who conducted a week long basketball camp in Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   ''To say he feels badly is an understatement,'' Olson said.
''There's no question about his feelings in terms of what he's done
to himself, primarily, but also the position that he placed the
basketball program in.''
</P>
<P>
   Terry knew that what he did was wrong, Olson said.
</P>
<P>
   Terry will be ineligible for the university's sports hall of
fame and to have his jersey number retired, which Arizona now does
for players named national player of the year. Terry was voted that
honor by at least two organizations.
</P>
<P>
   He admitted receiving cash, checks and wire transfers from Fox
and attended a fitness camp in Florida in August 1998 that Fox
arranged, but Terry never was billed for the airfare or camp fees,
Livengood said.
</P>
<P>
   Both agents have denied making payments to Terry, the university
said.
</P>
<P>
   Livengood said Terry and his mother, Andrea Cheatham, said Opia
also gave him legal advice without charge and had helped arrange
for catastrophic injury insurance, both considered preferential
treatment for a college athlete.
</P>
<P>
   The university began an 11-month investigation after Terry's
mother sent a letter to the National Basketball Players Association
on April 8, 1999, suggesting improprieties concerning extra
benefits for a student-athlete. A copy had been faxed to assistant
basketball coach Jim Rosborough three days earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Rosborough said he told NCAA investigators he first considered
the allegations ''flat-out, unequivocal hogwash. Pure baloney.''
Terry initially denied them, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The university subsequently reprimanded Rosborough because he
waited about three days before notifying Livengood about the
letter. Rosborough acknowledged he should have notified Livengood
immediately.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
