<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senate gives final approval to funds for Korean War memorial  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - The state Senate voted Thursday to put the
final $500,000 in place for a Korean War veterans memorial in
Atlantic City.
</P>
<P>
   The memorial will feature a 12-foot statue of a mourning soldier
clutching dog tags. To his left, two soldiers and a nurse will be
seen emerging through a sheet of water that cascades into a
reflecting pool.
</P>
<P>
   Also planned is an eternal flame above a wall featuring the
names of the New Jersey people who died or were missing in action
during the conflict, which lasted from 1950 to 1953.
</P>
<P>
   ''This site is a place where family and friends can reflect upon
the sacrifices made by the men and women of our armed forces,''
said state Sen. Louis F. Kosco, R-Bergen.
</P>
<P>
   Private funds contributed to building the memorial, but
supporters fell $500,000 short.
</P>
<P>
   When the memorial was conceived several years ago, it was
originally hoped that it could be dedicated on June 25, the 50th
anniversary of the start of the war. But thanks to construction
delays and other problems, that target date could not be met.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the most recent delays, organizers do not have a date
scheduled, although they hope the memorial can be unveiled in the
fall.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
