<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FCC Nears Bell Long-Distance Ruling  </HEADLINE>
By KALPANA SRINIVASAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal regulators, for only the second time,
are on the verge of allowing a Bell company to offer long-distance
telephone service to its local customers.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Communications Commission is expected to approve the
bid by SBC Communications to provide long-distance in Texas, one of
the states within its local calling region.
</P>
<P>
   The commission has until Wednesday to issue its decision, but
experts have widely predicted that SBC would receive regulatory
approval, and on Thursday, a Texas House lawmaker said a majority
of the commissioners had approved the application.
</P>
<P>
   The congressman, Rep. Gene Green, D-Texas, said in a Thursday
afternoon press release that the commission had approved the deal.
Green said his office was notified early in the day that an
announcement was imminent.
</P>
<P>
   Green said other lawmakers, including Rep. John Dingell of
Michigan, top Democrat on the Commerce Committee, received similar
word from the FCC. Dingell's staff confirmed that they were
contacted by the commission.
</P>
<P>
   Green said he spoke personally with FCC Chairman William Kennard
in the afternoon. Based on that conversation, Green said he
understood that a majority of the commissioners had voted to
approve the application
</P>
<P>
   ''I think SBC will be given the right to enter long-distance,''
Green said. ''That's good for Texas and the people I represent.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he thinks a final announcement may not come until next
week.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day, FCC officials asserted that no final action
had been taken yet. Commission actions do not become final until
all five members have voted.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will have a commission action on this soon,'' said FCC
spokeswoman Joy Howell.
</P>
<P>
   SBC spokesman Matt Miller said the company had not been notified
of any decision.
</P>
<P>
   SBC's application has been bolstered by support from the Justice
Department and Texas state regulators. Although the FCC has the
final word, it must give weight to both evaluations.
</P>
<P>
   The outlook for the application seemed particularly favorable
since the Justice Department gave its recommendation. It marked the
first time the department has backed a Bell company's attempt to
offer long-distance service within its local calling region.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department originally recommended that SBC's
application, filed at the beginning of this year, be denied. Bell
companies must satisfy a 14-point checklist meant to ensure their
market is open to rivals before they get approval to offer
long-distance.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department supported the application after it said
the company provided data showing it improved handling rivals'
requests to use its lines for high-speed Internet service. SBC also
improved the processing of orders to switch local phone customers
to competitors, the department said.
</P>
<P>
   The 1996 telecommunications law sought to increase competition
in local markets by allowing Bell companies to offer long-distance
service if they opened local service to competitors. The approval
would be another step toward that goal.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic became the first company to secure FCC permission
to offer its local customers long-distance calling last year,
earning that right in New York state.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-29-00 2023 </TRAILER>
