<DOCNO> APW20000629.0146 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Last C-141s leaving Charleston Air Force Base  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) - The end of an era is at hand at the
Charleston Air Force Base as the last C-141s flying out of
Charleston are retired after decades of service as the transport
workhorse of the Air Force.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the last Air Force Reserve squadron at the base to
fly the planes - the 707th Airlift Squadron - said goodbye to the
aircraft on Wednesday as the members were drenched in water and in
champagne. The squadron will be deactivated Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The 16th Airlift Squadron, the last active-duty squadron to fly
the planes, will be deactivated on July 15.
</P>
<P>
   The C-141s, which first came to Charleston 35 years ago, are
being retired throughout the Air Force, replaced by the newer
C-17s.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've been flying C-141s at Charleston since 1971,'' said
Senior Master Sgt. Bobby Jameson of North Charleston who retires
Friday after a career that spanned from Vietnam to Bosnia with the
Persian Gulf War and Grenada in between.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've had a few scary moments,'' he said, adding those moments
came from a few near midair collisions, not with problems with the
aircraft. ''It's been a good, safe airplane.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, there was one two-aircraft flyover of the base.
Then the reserve crews were doused by base fire trucks dousing the
planes, then with a bottle of champagne. Only six of the planes
remain in Charleston.
</P>
<P>
   Some bases, such as McGuire Air Force Base, N.J., will continue
flying C-141s for a few years. But by 2005, only certain reserve
and Air National Guard units will have the planes.
</P>
<P>
   The flyover was nostalgic for Larry Laverne, a retired Air Force
Reserve C-141 pilot from Atlanta. His son, Capt. Mark Laverne of
Marietta, Ga., flew one of the planes Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mark was 2 years old when I took him aboard the same aircraft
that he's flying today,'' the elder Laverne said. ''Now he's in the
same squadron I flew in. I would never have thought this could
happen when I started flying them 32 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   The younger Laverne said he would probably start flying C-17s
now as a reservist. In his civilian job he flies Boeing 727s for
United Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   The 707th squadron flew for 28 years - a total of 110,000 flying
hours - without an accident. The squadron will cease to exist on
Friday when it folds its unit colors during a retreat ceremony.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
