<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Seat Belts Used As Accessory  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   OSLO, Norway (AP) -- Airplane passengers are taking requirements
to wear their seat belts a little too literally, nabbing the canvas
straps to hold up their pants, Norway's largest domestic carrier
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The industrial-looking belts with the hefty metal clasp have
become high fashion for Norwegian youths and their extremely baggy
pants, and are disappearing from the company's planes at a rate of
about five a day, Braathens airline spokesman Stig Martin Solberg
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''What we know is that it is in fashion for the street look,''
Solberg said. ''It is easy to spot people on the street with
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Fashion stores offer similar belts, but the real thing seems to
have more status. The privately owned airline has been losing seat
belts for a year, and the situation has gotten worse, Solberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Several suspects have been caught and reported to the police.
The airline was also making it harder to remove the belts, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The belts cost only about $30 to replace, but the real expense
can be much higher -- particularly if a passenger is left without a
belt during flight or if a flight has to be delayed.
</P>
<P>
   The airline was considering suing seat-belt thieves for those
costs, which could make the straps one of the season's most
expensive fashions, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
