<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 20:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Quinnipiac College to become university after growth phase  </HEADLINE>
By DIANE SCARPONI
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAMDEN, Conn. (AP) - Quinnipiac College's 15-year transformation
from a small, rural school to a well-known name in health care,
media, law and politics will culminate Saturday in one more change.
</P>
<P>
   From then on, the school will be known as Quinnipiac University.
</P>
<P>
   The name change actually is the smallest transformation the
school has seen since it was founded as a junior college commuter
school in New Haven in 1929.
</P>
<P>
   It's part of a strategy to make Quinnipiac more competitive in a
region crowded with top colleges, said university President John L.
Lahey.
</P>
<P>
   ''Quinnipiac had very solid academic programs, especially in
business and health, but it was not marketed well. We were not too
well-known outside of Connecticut,'' Lahey said.
</P>
<P>
   Economics Professor Mark Gius, who is chairman of the faculty
Senate, said Quinnipiac really became a university years ago, when
it absorbed the old University of Bridgeport law school and many
graduate programs.
</P>
<P>
   ''By changing the name to Quinnipiac University, we're telling
the world we no longer are a little tiny college,'' Gius said.
</P>
<P>
   Some school activities, especially the polling institute that
operates in New York, New Jersey and Connecticut, has helped make
Quinnipiac a national name.
</P>
<P>
   Class of 2000 graduate Justin Louis said when he came to
Quinnipiac from Highland Park, N.J., no one had heard of the
school.
</P>
<P>
   ''The poll was just getting started, and people would say 'It's
Quinna-what?''' Louis recalled. Now, he said, people say they hear
about his alma mater all the time.
</P>
<P>
   Like many students, Louis was drawn by the 200-acre campus in
the shadow of Sleeping Giant State Park.
</P>
<P>
   Some new brick buildings sport the names of famous donors:
television personality Ed McMahon and bagel entrepreneur Murray
Lender.
</P>
<P>
   A new $6 million library is nearly complete, and building will
begin soon for a sports complex and graduate campus.
</P>
<P>
   Enrollment has doubled in 10 years, to 6,000, and new degrees
and programs were added in fields few area schools offer, such as
masters' degrees in journalism and degrees in forensic nursing.
</P>
<P>
   Its teams are competing at the top college level - Division 1A -
in selected sports that appeal to prospective students such as
lacrosse and ice hockey.
</P>
<P>
   When Lahey arrived at Quinnipiac in 1987 about two-thirds of the
students were from Connecticut, and many were commuters.
</P>
<P>
   Today, 30 percent of Quinnipiac's students are from New York, 15
percent are from New Jersey and 25 percent are from Connecticut;
almost all live on campus.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout it all Quinnipiac has remained a hands-on college
that helps students get good jobs, as opposed to the liberal arts
or research focus of schools such as Yale, UConn or Wesleyan
University.
</P>
<P>
   Gius said a few professors balked at the name change because
they feared it would alter the school's tradition of small classes,
taught by professors and not graduate students. Lahey and others
assured them that the traditions would not change.
</P>
<P>
   Quinnipiac took advantage of the last recession to offer
competitive pay to professors who were at schools facing cutbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Wesleyan President Douglas Bennet said he has watched with
admiration as Quinnipiac transformed itself.
</P>
<P>
   ''Any institution of any kind needs to be asking themselves
these kinds of strategic questions. It's a sign of, I think,
terrific institutional health when the institutions are able to
actually implement them,'' Bennet said.
</P>
<P>
   But Quinnipiac has its growing pains.
</P>
<P>
   It remains a mostly white, upper-middle-class school. About 8
percent of undergraduates are racial minorities, and 14 percent of
law school students are minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Academically, freshmen are middle-of-the-road. The average SAT
score for the 1999 freshman class was 1080, a little better than
the national average that year of 1016.
</P>
<P>
   As at most colleges, tuition at Quinnipiac increased through the
'90s. Undergraduate tuition is $17,000 for the coming school year;
with room and board, the price tag is almost $26,000, compared with
$14,200 a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   About 65 percent of students get some kind of financial aid.
Because of Quinnipiac's small endowment and competition for some
programs, financial aid falls behind schools such as Wesleyan,
which admits students regardless of their ability to pay.
</P>
<P>
   The wealth of some students gets noticed. Gius said a student
once dropped off his deposit after flying to Connecticut by
helicopter. A joke around campus is that the cars in the student
parking lot are nicer than the cars in the faculty parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   The endowment, while still small, has grown from $5 million to
$60 million. Lahey said his goal in the next few years is $100
million.
</P>
<P>
   ''If they want to be financially viable, we're really going to
have to do it,'' Gius said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-29-00 2042 </TRAILER>
