<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 20:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Faces Hard Mideast Decision  </HEADLINE>
By BARRY SCHWEID
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- Tangled in intractable discord, Israel and the
Palestinians are leaving it to President Clinton to decide whether
to host a Mideast summit or find some other formula to keep peace
talks alive. The president said Thursday he had not decided how to
proceed.
</P>
<P>
   After a brief run of shuttle diplomacy, Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright found the two sides far apart on Palestinian
statehood, the future of Jerusalem and other knotty issues they had
vowed to settle by mid-September.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's determination to score in the history books becomes a
larger factor as the clock ticks down on his White House years. He
has less than seven months left in office and a senior U.S.
official said Thursday he was prepared to mediate between Israeli
Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat
until his last days in office.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm going to do whatever I can in the time I have left to help
them make peace,'' Clinton said in an Oval Office ceremony as he
named former Rep. Norman Mineta as the new commerce secretary. ''So
whatever I do or don't do will be based on my calculation that it
will maximize the possibilities of ultimate success. But I don't
know yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day, the president was debriefed for 45 minutes by
Albright and Dennis Ross, a senior U.S. mediator in the
negotiations. White House spokesman P.J. Crowley declined to
divulge specifics of Albright's conversation with the president,
saying only: ''It was not a decision meeting. I think that her
focus was on the Palestinian front.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the wide gap, Albright left open the possibility Clinton
would call a summit. She stopped here to make a speech on prospects
for democracy in the Balkans and then headed home to report to the
president.
</P>
<P>
   Albright's summit strategy a week ago was to try to limit the
risk of failure by holding off on invitations until the two sides
were closer to an accord. She was unable to move them, but Clinton
could decide to go ahead anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton could make a decision as early as the weekend, said a
senior U.S. official, speaking on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   On the plane home to the United States, she told reporters she
would see the president Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are trying to find out what flexibility there is,'' said
Albright, adding that the parties are trying to make sure ''their
own ultimate goals are met.''
</P>
<P>
   She indicated that a summit may not be imminent but President
Clinton intends to see the process through until his very last day
in office. ''We have plenty of time to do what needs to be done,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, at a White House news conference, Clinton said the
issues would not ''get any easier with the passage of time.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the time was right for him to host a summit, Clinton
said none had been scheduled. He added, however, ''I do not believe
that they can resolve the final most difficult issues without
having the leaders get together in some isolated setting and make
the last tough decisions, or decide not to make them, as the case
may be.''
</P>
<P>
   The rhetoric from both sides was sharp as Albright shuttled
between Jerusalem and Ramallah on the West Bank, meeting with
Israeli and Palestinian leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat said, ''It's time for the
Israeli government to prepare its people'' for the steps needed to
make peace.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy urged the Palestinians to
compromise and halt ''inflammatory speeches and declarations.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright said the disagreement between Israel and the
Palestinian Authority ''does not mean everything stops.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It is critical that the parties continue their efforts with
one another to narrow the gaps,'' Albright said at a joint news
conference with Yasser Arafat in Ramallah on the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Erekat, in an interview, said lower-level negotiations with
Israel would resume in Washington next week, with Clinton to make
an assessment on a summit two or three weeks later.
</P>
<P>
   However, a State Department official, briefing reporters on
condition of anonymity, said there was no agreement to resume the
lower-level talks.
</P>
<P>
   Erekat described the gaps with Israel as ''enormous.''
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference, after a 70-minute meeting with Albright,
Barak expressed skepticism that his differences with Arafat could
be resolved except possibly at a summit, with Clinton's direct
intervention.
</P>
<P>
   ''The substantial negotiations will begin only if and when there
will be a summit meeting,'' Barak said. And, he went on, ''we will
negotiate only an agreement that will strengthen Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the prospects for a summit, it was clear that
Albright's separate talks with Barak and Arafat over two days had
made no dent in their stands on how much land Israel would transfer
to the Palestinians, the future of Jerusalem and the claims of
Palestinian refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat insisted Israel must turn over all of the West Bank, Gaza
and East Jerusalem for a Palestinian state. Barak, however, said
''agreement can be reached only if movement and flexibility will be
shown from both sides.''
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting deep disagreement seven years after negotiations
began, Israeli Foreign Minister Levy dismissed Arafat's demands.
''This would be capitulation'' and not ''a process of peace.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-29-00 2051 </TRAILER>
