<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 20:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Ranks Quality of Life  </HEADLINE>
By GEIR MOULSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA (AP) -- Twenty-four African countries trail the rest of
the world in quality of life, with Sierra Leone lodged at rock
bottom, according to a United Nations report released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   As ministers at a special General Assembly meeting in Geneva
thrashed out a statement on eradicating world poverty, a Human
Development Report identified 35 countries as suffering from ''low
development'' -- all but six of them in sub-Saharan Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Canada topped the list of the 174-country Human Development
Index, which takes into account income, education, life expectancy
and health care. It was followed, as last year, by Norway and the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   The 150th-ranked Haiti was the worst-performing nation in the
Americas. Japan was the top Asian country, in ninth place, while
Bangladesh was the lowest, in 146th place.
</P>
<P>
   War-ravaged Sierra Leone, where a male's life expectancy is only
36&AMP;frac12; years, followed Niger and Burkina Faso at the bottom of the
list.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations says some 1.2 billion people live in absolute
poverty -- on less than a dollar a day -- and aims to halve that
number by 2015.
</P>
<P>
   But improving the lot of the people of the world means focusing
on a wider range of issues, according to the study, produced by the
U.N. Development Fund. The way governments respect individual
rights, for example, was just as important as how much money people
had.
</P>
<P>
   ''Holding governments accountable is a bottom-line
requirement,'' even as globalization advances, the 290-page study
said.
</P>
<P>
   The top U.N. authority on human rights, Mary Robinson, welcomed
the report: ''Human rights and economic and social progress are
inextricably linked,'' she said. ''For far too long we have looked
at development and human rights separately.''
</P>
<P>
   Pope John Paul II, noting the report, called the fight against
poverty ''one of the biggest challenges facing humanity in the new
millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Necessary food, health assistance, education and work do not
represent only objectives of development,'' the pope told pilgrims
gathered in St. Peter's Square on Thursday. ''They are fundamental
rights still denied, unfortunately, to millions of human beings.''
</P>
<P>
   Of 101 nations tracked since 1975, all but Zambia improved their
score in the index. However, 22 countries -- mostly in Africa and
East Europe -- saw their scores diminished since 1990, mostly due to
the AIDS epidemic, economic stagnation and violent conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ''AIDS is clearly an unprecedented development crisis which is
undermining achievement in social development,'' said Kathleen
Cravero, deputy executive director of the joint U.N. program on
HIV/AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   The report noted that more than 100 multiparty democracies have
been established in the past 20 years, but they were of varying
quality.
</P>
<P>
   President Olusegun Obasanjo of 151st-placed Nigeria said,
though, that democracy alone was not enough to motivate people to
lift themselves out of poverty.
</P>
<P>
   ''Democracy is an imperative, not a luxury, and it has come to
stay,'' he told reporters. But ''we must have the resources to be
able to give our people what I call a democracy dividend.''
Obasanjo urged rich countries to write off more of the developing
world's debt and offer more development assistance.
</P>
<P>
   The picture wasn't entirely rosy for the highest-ranked nations,
where the report noted problems of adult illiteracy and
unemployment. In Britain, the United States and Ireland, more than
one in five adults are functionally illiterate, meaning that they
read below fifth-grade level, the study said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.undp.org
</P>
<P>
   http://www.un.org/socialsummit
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-29-00 2052 </TRAILER>
