<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Smith Corona will sell stock, keep assets  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CORTLAND, N.Y. (AP) - A month after declaring bankruptcy and
announcing it would shed its assets, typewriter maker Smith Corona
said Thursday it will sell 49 percent of its stock and retain its
name.
</P>
<P>
   The stock purchase with Pubco Corp., a Cleveland-based
manufacturer of thermal printers and thermal and impact printer
supplies, is part of Smith Corona's ongoing reorganization plan and
replaces an earlier deal with Carolina Wholesale Office Machine Co.
</P>
<P>
   The original deal, announced in May, had Carolina buying all of
Smith Corona's assets including inventory, accounts receivable,
intellectual property, equipment, dies and molds and certain
contracts and licenses in a deal valued at about $6 million.
</P>
<P>
   Smith Corona spokeswoman Rivian Bell said a value of the Pubco
stock purchase has not been determined but said it was a ''higher
and better offer'' than the Carolina deal.
</P>
<P>
   Under terms of the agreement, approved in bankruptcy court,
Smith Corona would be reorganized under Chapter 11 and continue to
exist as an ongoing entity. Upon completion of the Chapter 11
proceeding, Pubco would buy 49 percent of the stock in the
reorganized Smith Corona.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining 51 percent of the new common stock would be issued
to creditors and, if allowed by the court, to stockholders.
</P>
<P>
   Pubco also would take over Smith Corona's secured debt.
</P>
<P>
   ''The stock purchase agreement with Pubco provides more value to
satisfy creditor claims than the Carloina Wholesale asset purchase
deal,'' said Martin D. Wilson, president and chief executive
officer of Smith Corona. ''In addition, Smith Corona's business
will continue to operate under the Smith Corona name with the
opportunity to introduce products of the Pubco companies through
the Smith Corona distribution channels.''
</P>
<P>
   The reorganization plan should be final by December, Bell said.
</P>
<P>
   May's bankruptcy filing was the second time in five years the
troubled 97-year-old company sought protection from its creditors
under federal bankruptcy laws. In April, Smith Corona was dropped
from the Nasdaq stock listings.
</P>
<P>
   The filing listed $14.4 million in liabilities and $12.4 million
in assets.
</P>
<P>
   Smith Corona stopped making products when it emerged from
Chapter 11 bankruptcy proceedings in 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
