<DOCNO> APW20000629.0159 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 21:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arizona's Stottlemyre Eyes Return  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX (AP) -- Todd Stottlemyre already has made one amazing
comeback. Now he hopes to make another.
</P>
<P>
   One year after returning sooner than expected from two tears in
his right rotator cuff, the 35-year-old right-hander is hoping to
return early from an elbow injury.
</P>
<P>
   ''If there's a chance that I can pitch like I did two starts ago
and pitch those kind of games in September, that's what I'm going
to do,'' Stottlemyre said Thursday before the Arizona Diamondbacks
played the Houston Astros. ''If I was going to bet, I'd bet that I
was going to be back in September.''
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre was placed on the 15-day disabled list Monday with
tendinitis in his right elbow.
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre originally had been told he'd miss only three weeks
because of this second recurrence of tendinitis. But that estimate
was pushed back on Wednesday after an examination by team doctor
David Zeman also revealed a microscopic muscle tear.
</P>
<P>
   Zeman said on Wednesday that such a soft tissue injury normally
requires two months of rest to heal.
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre was on the disabled list from May 30 to June 14 with
the same ailment. He came back for two strong starts, but took
himself out of the game after the first inning of Sunday's game
against Colorado because of intense pain.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was a little concerned with the amount of pain I had in the
first inning but I wasn't going to jump to any conclusions until I
knew the results,'' said Stottlemyre, who is 8-5 with 4.24 ERA. ''I
think everyone knew I was waiting for him (Zeman) to get back into
town. The relationship we developed has gone beyond doctor-patient.
I listened to what he had to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre was adamant that this injury was unrelated to the
rotator cuff tears that sidelined him for three months last season.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't have anything wrong with my shoulder,'' said
Stottlemyre, who opted to begin an intense weightlifting program
rather than undergo season-ending surgery last year. ''My shoulder
today with two tears is stronger at 35 than it was with no tears at
22. When it's time for them to start digging in my shoulder, I'm
going to be doing something different.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Stottlemyre had admitted he had considered
retirement but loved playing for the Diamondbacks and owner Jerry
Colangelo and wanted to help them win a championship.
</P>
<P>
   Any such thoughts since have been pushed to the back of his
mind, Stottlemyre said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Each time on the DL gets a little more frustrating,''
Stottlemyre said. ''But I'm passing on any of those thoughts until
something's conclusive, until I'm not capable of going out there
and pitching or not capable of going out there and putting together
a full season.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Morgan, the 40-year-old veteran signed this spring as a
long reliever and emergency starter, will take Stottlemyre's turn
in the rotation Friday when the Diamondbacks open a four-game
series against the Cincinnati Reds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-29-00 2112 </TRAILER>
