<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OAS To Oversee Reforms From Lima  </HEADLINE>
By MONTE HAYES
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru (AP) -- The Organization of American States said
Thursday that it will set up a permanent office in Lima to oversee
democratic reforms following President Alberto Fujimori's
re-election, which some local and international groups charged was
tainted.
</P>
<P>
   A high-level OAS delegation said Fujimori and government
opponents had agreed with its agenda to strengthen the country's
damaged democracy and the permanent office would supervise the
process.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will be establishing an ongoing mission here in Peru to
maintain an OAS presence,'' said Canadian Foreign Minister Lloyd
Axworthy, co-leader of the OAS delegation. ''A lot more work needs
to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   OAS Secretary General Cesar Gaviria, the other leader of the
mission, said the agenda had been accepted by both sides ''and we
will try to advance in the process in terms of the mechanisms and a
realistic timetable for carrying out the reforms.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday Foreign Minister Fernando de Trazegnies had
rejected any demand for a timetable, but Gaviria insisted a
schedule had to be established for implementing the reforms.
</P>
<P>
   ''At the latest we expect this process to be concluded before
the next municipal elections'' at the end of 2002, Gaviria said at
a news conference at the end of a two-day visit to Peru.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition leader Alejandro Toledo, who boycotted the May 28
presidential runoff after charging that Fujimori planned to rig the
outcome, praised the OAS success in establishing an agenda aimed at
strengthening Peru's democratic institutions.
</P>
<P>
   ''The democratic forces of Peru have achieved a great victory,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The OAS agenda calls for reforms to establish an independent
judicial system, guarantee press freedom, correct flaws in the
electoral process and provide oversight of the armed forces and
intelligence services, which have been key allies in helping
Fujimori tighten his grip on all branches of government.
</P>
<P>
   The government had no comment Thursday on the OAS announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo has been pressing the OAS to force Fujimori to call new
elections, and he reiterated Thursday that he expects the reforms
''to lead inevitably to a new election.''
</P>
<P>
   But the OAS mission has said that its mandate is to push for
democratic reforms, not new elections, because without substantial
changes new elections would produce the same flawed results.
</P>
<P>
   Early Thursday, police used tear gas to prevent Toledo from
leading some 1,500 supporters in a march to the luxury hotel being
used by the OAS delegation.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstrators were stopped three blocks shy of the hotel in
the heart of Lima's business district shortly after midnight. They
responded by hurling rocks and burning tires and garbage in the
streets.
</P>
<P>
   Cable news station Canal N reported at least five people
injured, including a local reporter struck in the face with a rock.
Police at the scene confirmed that injuries occurred, but could not
provide details. No arrests were reported.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori pledged to fortify Peru's democratic institutions after
winning an unprecedented third five-year term, following a campaign
riddled with irregularities and allegations of government fraud.
</P>
<P>
   The OAS refused to monitor the May 28 ballot after Fujimori
refused to delay it and correct irregularities, but sent the
follow-up delegation to ensure Fujimori keeps his postelection
promise.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-29-00 2122 </TRAILER>
