<HEADLINE> Cleveland's Colon Walks First Four  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- Cleveland's Bartolo Colon became just
the fourth pitcher in history to walk the first four batters in a
game Thursday night, tying the major league record.
</P>
<P>
   The right-hander walked Kansas City's Johnny Damon, Jeff
Reboulet and Mike Sweeney, loading the bases. Then on a 3-2 count,
he walked Jermaine Dye.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Quinn had a sacrifice fly and Joe Randa an RBI fielder's
choice, giving the Royals three runs in the inning without getting
a hit.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 37 pitches Colon threw in the inning, 20 were balls.
</P>
<P>
   The last time a pitcher began a game by walking the first four
hitters was April 18, 1997 by Roger Pavlik of Texas.
</P>
</TEXT>
