<HEADLINE> Coleman Testifies at Umpires Hearing  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Former National League president Len Coleman
testified Thursday as the grievance resumed for 22 umpires trying
to regain their job.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman issued the decisions last summer of which 13 NL umpires
were let go among the 34 who submitted resignations. He resigned
late last year after commissioner Bud Selig and baseball owners
decided to eliminate the position of league president, effective
with the 2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman was due back Friday before arbitrator Alan Symonette.
While lawyers originally thought testimony would wrap up this week,
it now appears the case will stretch into next month, with
additional hearing dates set for July 14-16.
</P>
<P>
   After owners released the 22 umpires, including nine from the
American League, Richie Phillips' Major League Umpires Association
filed a grievance in an attempt to regain their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   While umpires replaced the MLUA during the offseason with the
World Umpires Association, dominated by AL umpires who opposed
Phillips, federal labor law calls for the old union to argue the
grievance.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, owners have offered during current bargaining a new
labor contract to rehire an unspecified number of the 22 umps. The
next bargaining session is scheduled for July 5.
</P>
</TEXT>
