<HEADLINE> Mets' Reed Fractures Left Wrist  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- New York Mets right-hander Rick Reed fractured
his left wrist Thursday night when Atlanta's Andruw Jones lined a
single off him in the third inning.
</P>
<P>
   Reed grounded out in the bottom of the inning, then left the
game. He was scheduled to be examined Friday.
</P>
<P>
   He allowed four runs and five hits in three innings, leaving
with the Mets trailing 4-2 after New York scored two runs in the
bottom of the third.
</P>
<P>
   On April 19, Reed was hit on the left hand by a liner off the
bat of Milwaukee's Marquis Grissom. Reed also sprained his right
wrist in the game. On May 27, he strained a muscle on his left side
pitching against St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, he went on the disabled list twice, from April 12-May
3 with a slightly torn left calf muscle and from Aug. 9-Sept. 4
with a strained ligament in the middle finger of his pitching hand.
</P>
<P>
   Reed, 34, has a 4.76 ERA, entering the game with a 4-1 record.
</P>
