<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 21:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Volcano Evacuation Order Lifted  </HEADLINE>
By YURI KAGEYAMA
<TEXT>
<P>
   KAMITSUKI, Japan (AP) -- Almost 2,000 people returned to their
homes on a Japanese island island after experts determined that the
chances of a volcano erupting had subsided, officials said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   However, mild earthquakes continued to shake the island in the
Pacific Ocean, 120 miles south of Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   Officials partially lifted an evacuation order for the island's
southeastern district of Tsubota Thursday evening and the other
affected areas of the island a few hours later.
</P>
<P>
   Seiji Asanuma, a town official of Miyakejima, said Friday that
all but a few elderly at nursing homes returned to their homes by
around 10:00 p.m. Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The lifting of the evacuation order followed an announcement by
seismologists in Tokyo Thursday afternoon said chances of an
eruption had subsided.
</P>
<P>
   ''The level of volcanic activity is declining, and there is
almost no chance of eruption that would affect the ground level or
the ocean,'' Hitoshi Takeuchi, a seismologist at the government's
Coordinating Committee for the Prediction of Volcanic Eruptions,
told a news conference nationally televised on the nation's
semi-public NHK.
</P>
<P>
   Takeuchi, however, warned Thursday of continuing earthquakes
centered in the waters off the west coast of the island.
</P>
<P>
   Islanders had spent three hot and humid nights at shelters on
the island's northern district of Kamitsuki, said Miyakejima
spokesman Satoshi Enomoto.
</P>
<P>
   The evacuation order was issued Monday to about half of the
4,000 people living on the island after intensifying earthquakes
signaled a possible eruption on Miyakejima, also the name of a
2,686-foot volcano.
</P>
<P>
   Miyakejima has erupted several times in the last 60 years,
including in 1983, but the blasts usually came quickly and were
over in a couple of days.
</P>
<P>
   No one was killed or injured in the last eruption because
residents were evacuated in time. Eleven people died, and 20 were
injured in a 1940 eruption.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
