<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 22:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Thursday, June 29, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Senate OKs Limited Patient Rights
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Republican-controlled Senate voted largely along party
lines tonight, 51-47, for limited new patient protections, including a
restricted right to sue HMOs. Democrats had called the plan an election-year
sham. The vote capped two weeks of intense partisanship in both the House and
Senate over health care issues expected to resonate in the fall campaign. Senate
GOP Whip Don Nickles, R-Okla., said the proposal marked a ''significant
concession'' over legislation that Republicans approved last year that barred
lawsuits.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Illinois Suspends Gas Tax
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SPRINGFIELD, Ill. (AP) -- Driven by some of the highest gasoline prices in
the nation, Illinois today became the second state to suspend its sales tax on
gas. Legislators, voting in a special session, urged gas stations to pass along
the 5 percent tax savings on the gasoline they sell. If they do, drivers could
see prices fall by 7 or 8 cents a gallon in a state where prices in some areas
have soared well above $2 per gallon. The legislation, which was quickly signed
by Gov. George Ryan, suspends the tax for six months, starting Saturday, and
requires each gas pump to display a sign saying the tax has been lowered and
that prices should reflect the change.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
House OKs Colombia, Disaster Funds
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Leaders resolved a last-minute snag today and whisked
through the House an $11.2 billion emergency package bearing money for
Colombia's drug war, the Pentagon and storm victims at home. Months in the
making, the bill was approved by a bipartisan margin of 306-110. The Senate was
all but certain to give it final approval tomorrow, when Congress' Fourth of
July break is scheduled to begin. White House budget director Jack Lew signaled
that President Clinton would sign the measure.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
FCC Close To Approving Long-Distance Bid
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal regulators, for only the second time, are on the
verge of allowing a Bell company to offer long-distance telephone service to its
local customers. The Federal Communications Commission is expected to approve
the bid by SBC Communications to provide long-distance in Texas, one of the
states within its local calling region. The commission has until Wednesday to
issue its decision, but experts have widely predicted that SBC would receive
regulatory approval, and on Thursday, a Texas House lawmaker said a majority of
the commissioners had approved the application.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Fire Roars at Wash. Nuke Reservation
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   RICHLAND, Wash. (AP) -- A wildfire ignited by a car crash raged across the
dry sagebrush of the Hanford nuclear complex today, raising fears that the
flames would spread radioactive material. At least 25 homes were destroyed, and
about 7,000 people were driven from their homes by the second blaze in two
months to threaten a U.S. nuclear weapons installation. The fire, which began
Tuesday, had scorched 190,000 acres and the National Weather Service warned of
wind up to 30 mph and a continuation of 100-degree temperatures.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Man Has Hostages at Disney World
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LAKE BUENA VISTA, Fla. (AP) -- A armed man held his 4-year-old son and a
waiter hostage today at a Walt Disney World hotel and demanded to speak to his
estranged wife, authorities said. Negotiators and a police psychologist talked
to the man and the hostage at the Boardwalk Inn, said a spokesman for the
sheriff's office. The waiter was taken hostage when he delivered food to the
man's hotel room. The man was identified by officials as 39-year-old Bismark
Rodriguez.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Faces Hard Mideast Decision
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- Tangled in intractable discord, Israel and the Palestinians
are leaving it to President Clinton to decide whether to host a Mideast summit
or find some other formula to keep peace talks alive. The president said today
he had not decided how to proceed. After a brief run of shuttle diplomacy,
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright found the two sides far apart on
Palestinian statehood, the future of Jerusalem and other knotty issues they had
vowed to settle by mid-September.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dow Ends Down 130; Nasdaq Falls 63
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks fell today on worries that rising interest rates are
cutting into corporate earnings. The Dow Jones industrial average fell 129.75 to
close at 10,398.04. On the NYSE, losers led gainers by a 10-9 margin. The Nasdaq
composite index was down 63.11 at 3,877.23.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Yankees' Deal Ends Pursuit of Sosa
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH (AP) -- The New York Yankees' pursuit of Chicago Cubs slugger
Sammy Sosa ended tonight when the Yankees traded for Cleveland outfielder David
Justice, according to Sosa's agent. The Yankees and Cubs stepped up negotiations
earlier this week after the Yankees' proposed deal for Juan Gonzalez fell
through, but the two teams could not agree on a package of players. Sosa's
agent, Tom Reich, still expects Sosa to be traded.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by RICHARD A. SOMMA
</SUBHEAD>
