<HEADLINE> Red Sox 12, Orioles 4  </HEADLINE>
By HOWARD ULMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) -- Brian Daubach snapped out of a slump with two
homers and six RBIs and Tim Wakefield pitched seven strong innings
as the Boston Red Sox broke a five-game losing streak with a 12-4
victory Thursday night over the Baltimore Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   Daubach, 10-for-67 in June, went 4-for-4 with a three-run homer
in the second inning and a solo shot in the seventh, giving him 13
homers for the season. He had a two-run double in the eighth. Scott
Hatteberg added a three-run homer in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing 8-0, Baltimore scored four in the eighth on Albert
Belle's three-run homer off Wakefield, his 18th of the season, and
pinch-hitter Jeff Conine's solo shot, his 10th, off Sang Lee.
Boston rallied for four runs in the bottom of the inning on a
bases-loaded walk to Jason Varitek, Daubach's double and Jose
Offerman's sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   Wakefield, who complained publicly about not starting after Jeff
Fassero went on the disabled list June 19, made it tougher for
manager Jimy Williams to return him to the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   In his fourth start of the year and first since June 3, he
struck out two and walked none in 7 1-3 innings, leaving after
Belle's homer. It was the ninth hit off Wakefield (3-5), who went
to three balls on just two batters.
</P>
<P>
   Wakefield is a victim of his own versatility, making 24 relief
appearances this year. But he had his best season with Boston as a
starter in 1998 when he went 17-8. And in his last three relief
outings this season, he allowed 12 earned runs in 7 1-3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Daubach gave Boston a 3-0 lead when he followed a single by
instant sensation Morgan Burkhart and a walk to Hatteberg with his
homer, a two-out shot off Scott Erickson (3-6).
</P>
<P>
   Offerman's sacrifice fly made it 4-0 in the fourth. In the next
inning, Hatteberg followed singles by Carl Everett and Burkhart
with his second homer.
</P>
<P>
   Burkhart, a 28-year-old rookie who played his first major league
game Tuesday night, quickly has become a fan favorite. The first
baseman-designated hitter went 2-for-2 with three walks and is
6-for-10 with four walks in three games. He's reached base in 11 of
his 14 plate appearances.
</P>
<P>
   He joined the Boston organization last year after four seasons
with the Richmond (Ind.) Roosters of the independent Frontier
League where he hit .404 with 36 homers in 80 games in 1998. With
Triple-A Pawtucket this season, he had 17 homers and 54 RBIs and
hit .283.
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles, who won the first two games of the series in extra
innings, lost for the 10th time in 12 games.
</P>
<P>
Notes: The Red Sox placed RHP Pedro Martinez on the 15-day
disabled list with shoulder and side problems. He can be activated
the day of the All-Star game, July 11. ... Boston extended a
dubious club record streak of allowing homers in 14 consecutive
games. ... Will Clark's eighth-inning double made it 72 games out
of 76 in which Baltimore got an extra-base hit. ... Boston ended
B.J. Surhoff's hitting streak at 21 games, matching his career
high. He was tied for the longest streak in the AL this year until
Toronto's Carlos Delgado stretched his to 22 Thursday afternoon.
... Nomar Garciaparra improved his AL-leading average to .390 by
going 2-for-4.
</P>
</TEXT>
