<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 22:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House OKs Los Alamos Relief  </HEADLINE>
By MATT KELLEY
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Seven weeks after fire destroyed hundreds of
homes in New Mexico, the House on Thursday approved $661 million in
compensation for residents and government agencies that suffered
losses.
</P>
<P>
   The package for New Mexico fire victims is part of a larger
package of spending including funding for military anti-drug
efforts in Colombia. The House approved it 306-110 Thursday night,
and the Senate was expected to pass the measure Friday before
leaving for the Fourth of July recess.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for President Clinton said he would sign the
measure.
</P>
<P>
   The National Park Service started a fire May 4 to clear brush in
Bandelier National Monument. That fire got out of control and a
backfire started to control the first got out of control itself,
becoming the Cerro Grande fire that burned 47,000 acres. The blaze
destroyed more than 200 homes in Los Alamos and burned over parts
of the Los Alamos nuclear weapons laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   New Mexico lawmakers say the measure is only the first step
toward paying for fire damage.
</P>
<P>
   ''Congress is ready to provide this and more compensation
funding if it is needed,'' said Sen. Pete Domenici, R-N.M.
</P>
<P>
   Park Service officials have acknowledged they are responsible
for the fire and apologized. Bandelier Superintendent Roy Weaver
was suspended and plans to retire Sunday. Park Service officials
have not determined whether anyone else will be disciplined for
their role in the fire.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Federal Emergency Management Agency:
http://www.fema.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
