<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Strong thunderstorms pummeled the Great Lakes and
Plains states
Thursday, causing hail and isolated flooding. Heavy rain also fell
in the Southeast.
<TEXT>
<P>
   A storm system in the central and southerain Plains produced
torainadoes in sections of Nebraska. No damage had been reported as
the storms raced in Kansas and Texas in the evening.
</P>
<P>
   Scattered flood watches and warainings were issued in Texas, which
had rain over the past several days. And a storm system in the
Great Lakes caused hail in lower Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   A frontal boundary extending from the mid-Atlantic Coast into
the Gulf states produced showers and thunderstorms that dumped
heavy rain in the region. By afterainoon, Wilmington, N.C., recorded
3.82 inches of rain.
</P>
<P>
   Cooler, drier air shifted into the southerain Ohio and Tennessee
Valleys. Parts of the Northeast dried out from rain earlier in the
week.
</P>
<P>
   A low pressure system coming off the Pacific lowered
temperatures in the Northwest. It remained hot one in Califorainia
and the Desert Southwest.
</P>
<P>
   Temperatures in the Lower 48 states Thursday ranged from an
afterainoon high of 109 degrees in Needles, Calif., to a moraining low
of 34 degrees in Orr., Minn.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
