<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 22:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House OKs Colombia, Disaster Funds  </HEADLINE>
By ALAN FRAM
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Leaders resolved a last-minute snag Thursday
and whisked through the House an $11.2 billion emergency package
bearing money for Colombia's drug war, the Pentagon and storm
victims at home.
</P>
<P>
   Months in the making, the bill was approved by a bipartisan
margin of 306-110. The Senate was all but certain to give it final
approval on Friday, when Congress' Fourth of July break is
scheduled to begin.
</P>
<P>
   Signaling that he would sign the measure, President Clinton said
afterward, ''While it contains certain flaws, in total this bill
will make our nation safer and more secure by meeting essential and
long-overdue needs at home and abroad.''
</P>
<P>
   The last impasse was broken after House Speaker Dennis Hastert,
R-Ill., relented and agreed to keep language off the bill lifting
food sanctions against Cuba. Senate opponents who said it did not
liberalize trade enough had threatened to derail the entire
spending bill unless it was free of the sanctions language.
</P>
<P>
   The Cuba provision, worked out earlier this week between
farm-state and anti-Castro lawmakers, will now await inclusion in
the final version of an agriculture spending bill later this
summer, aides said.
</P>
<P>
   The highlight of the emergency package was $1.3 billion to help
Colombia battle drug producers and their heavily armed guerrilla
allies, who control much of the southern part of the country.
Clinton and Hastert made that aid a priority as part of an effort
to stanch the flow of Colombian cocaine and heroin into the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Their combined drive for the money overcame opposition by
members of both parties. Opponents cited allegations of Colombian
human rights abuses, fear of U.S. involvement in an unwinnable,
four-decade-long conflict, and a preference to use the money for
drug prevention programs at home.
</P>
<P>
   ''A profound mistake,'' is how Rep. David Obey, D-Wis.,
described the Colombian aid.
</P>
<P>
   Most of that money is for purchasing 60 Blackhawk and Huey
helicopters for the Colombians, training and equipping
counternarcotics battalions, and intelligence activity. There would
also be money for human rights programs in Colombia, for Bolivia,
Ecuador and other nearby countries, and for U.S. aircraft
performing anti-drug surveillance.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is time for us to reach out a helping hand to Colombia,''
Hastert said afterward.
</P>
<P>
   But the election-year bill was also packed with hundreds of
millions of dollars for lawmakers' home districts. The House and
Senate each alloted $105 million for members' projects.
</P>
<P>
   A pair of U.S. Senate candidates -- Reps. Rick Lazio, R-N.Y., and
Bob Franks, R-N.J. -- had projects to boast about. Lazio was
trumpeting $6 million for homeless shelters nationwide, part of
which was going for a veterans' shelter in Buffalo, N.Y. Franks won
$41 million for New Jersey communities damaged by floods spawned by
last September's Hurricane Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   There was also $500,000 to extend a bicycle path in the northern
Virginia district of Rep. James Moran, D-Va.; $1 million to repair
a federal hurricane-chaser plane based in the Tampa district of
House Appropriations Committee Chairman Bill Young, R-Fla.; and $5
million to continue work on a sealife institute in Seward, Alaska,
home state of Senate Appropriations Committee Chairman Ted Stevens,
R-Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., top Democrat on the Appropriations
Committee, won $25 million for a federal firearms training center
and $7 million for Army research on computer security, both in his
home state. And there is $16 million to clean up uranium processing
plants in Kentucky and Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., won
language clearing the way for the $273 million Lewis and Clark
rural water system, which will serve the southeastern portion of
the state. The bill only supplied $600,000 for a study.
</P>
<P>
   The bill also included $2 billion to repay the Pentagon for the
costs of 5,700 U.S. members of the NATO peacekeeping team in
Kosovo. There was also $4.4 billion more for fuel, health care and
other Pentagon programs.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, there was $661 million for rebuilding from the
government-set fires that ravaged Los Alamos, N.M., and about $360
million to help North Carolina and other states recover from last
September's Hurricane Floyd and other agricultural problems.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton proposed a $5.2 billion package at the beginning of the
year, and the House approved its own $13 billion version in March.
But the bill ground to a halt in the Senate, where Majority Leader
Trent Lott, R-Miss., said it threatened to grow too large.
</P>
<P>
   But steady pressure for action was applied by Colombian
President Andres Pastrana and the Pentagon, which was facing budget
shortfalls because of the expenses of deploying U.S. troops as
peacekeepers in Kosovo. GOP leaders decided two weeks ago to try
finishing the bill before July.
</P>
<P>
   The emergency money was attached to a routine $8.8 billion
measure financing military construction projects for 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The bill is HR4425.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-29-00 2222 </TRAILER>
