<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 22:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Leaders Pledge To Protect Serbs  </HEADLINE>
By ELIDA RAMADANI
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- U.N. officials pledged Thursday to
take new steps to protect the Serb community in Kosovo, signing a
deal aimed at persuading moderate leaders to cooperate in
administering the province.
</P>
<P>
   The deal struck by the top U.N. official in Kosovo and a
prominent Serb cleric will create a special security task force to
protect the minority community, which has been targeted in the year
since NATO-led troops entered the province after a 78-day air war.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is an important moment,'' said the top U.N. official in
Kosovo, Bernard Kouchner. ''We have decided to improve the security
for all communities in Kosovo, mainly the Serbs.''
</P>
<P>
   Tens of thousands of Serbs have fled the province fearing
attacks leveled in revenge for Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic's decade-long campaign of repression against ethnic
Albanians. Dozens of attacks in recent weeks have only increased
concerns that alliance peacekeepers had failed to create the
conditions to allow Serbs to go home.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is important to Kouchner, in part because it allows him
to keep the moderate Serbs close to the day-to-day workings of the
province -- and avert an embarrassing retreat from the government.
Serb leaders had been pressuring the United Nations to act in light
of violence.
</P>
<P>
   Moderate Serbs agreed last Sunday to resume participation with
ethnic Albanians in the U.N. led interim government after the
second boycott of its workings in the past half year. The boycotts
were prompted by growing concern about the inability to stop
attacks on the dwindling Kosovo Serb community by ethnic Albanians
seeking to get even for the Serb crackdown that ended after
Milosevic pulled his troops out a year ago, and allowed NATO in.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal, the United Nations promised to improve its
efforts in the realm of criminal justice, promising to ''take
special measures, including the development of a neighborhood watch
system to maximize the protection and freedom of movement of the
Serb community in Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   The other measures include intensifying efforts to recruit and
train Serbs as part of the local police force; appointing more
international judges and prosecutors and creating a special
committee charged with overseeing the protection of religious
sites.
</P>
<P>
   The document also calls for getting local Kosovo Serb judges to
take part, along with foreign magistrates, in the
war-and-ethnic-crime tribunal to be established in Kosovo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-29-00 2255 </TRAILER>
