<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Thursday, June 29, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Senate OKs Limited Patient Rights
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Voting largely along party lines tonight, the
Republican-controlled Senate voted for limited new patient protections,
including a restricted right to sue HMOs. Democrats had called the plan an
election-year sham. The 51-47 vote capped two weeks of intense partisanship in
both the House and Senate over health care issues expected to resonate in the
fall campaign. Senate GOP Whip Don Nickles, R-Okla., said the proposal marked a
''significant concession'' over legislation that Republicans approved last year
that barred lawsuits.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Fire Roars at Wash. Nuke Reservation
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   RICHLAND, Wash. (AP) -- A wildfire ignited by a car crash raged across the
dry sagebrush of the Hanford nuclear complex today, raising fears that the
flames would spread radioactive material. At least 25 homes were destroyed, and
about 7,000 people were driven from their homes by the second blaze in two
months to threaten a U.S. nuclear weapons installation. The fire, which began
Tuesday, had scorched 190,000 acres and the National Weather Service warned of
wind up to 30 mph and a continuation of 100-degree temperatures.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Illinois Suspends Gas Tax
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SPRINGFIELD, Ill. (AP) -- Driven by some of the highest gasoline prices in
the nation, Illinois today became the second state to suspend its sales tax on
gas. Legislators, voting in a special session, urged gas stations to pass along
the 5 percent tax savings on the gasoline they sell. If they do, drivers could
see prices fall by 7 or 8 cents a gallon in a state where prices in some areas
have soared well above $2 per gallon. The legislation, which was quickly signed
by Gov. George Ryan, suspends the tax for six months, starting Saturday, and
requires each gas pump to display a sign saying the tax has been lowered and
that prices should reflect the change.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
House OKs Colombia, Disaster Funds
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Leaders resolved a last-minute snag today and whisked
through the House an $11.2 billion emergency package bearing money for
Colombia's drug war, the Pentagon and storm victims at home. Months in the
making, the bill was approved by a bipartisan margin of 306-110. The Senate was
all but certain to give it final approval tomorrow, when Congress' Fourth of
July break is scheduled to begin. White House budget director Jack Lew signaled
that President Clinton would sign the measure.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Man Has Hostages at Disney World
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LAKE BUENA VISTA, Fla. (AP) -- A armed man held his 4-year-old son and a
waiter hostage today at a Walt Disney World hotel and demanded to speak to his
estranged wife, authorities said. Negotiators and a police psychologist talked
to the man and the hostage at the Boardwalk Inn, said a spokesman for the
sheriff's office. The waiter was taken hostage when he delivered food to the
man's hotel room. The man was identified by officials as 39-year-old Bismark
Rodriguez.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
OAS To Oversee Reforms From Lima
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru (AP) -- The Organization of American States said Thursday that it
will set up a permanent office in Lima to oversee democratic reforms following
President Alberto Fujimori's re-election, which some local and international
groups charged was tainted. A high-level OAS delegation said Fujimori and
government opponents had agreed with its agenda to strengthen the country's
damaged democracy and the permanent office would supervise the process.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Guatemala Broadcasts Executions
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   GUATEMALA CITY (AP) -- In nationwide television broadcast, two members of a
Guatemalan kidnapping ring were executed by lethal injection Thursday. With
every channel in the Central American nation focused on the death penalties,
Guatemalans watched as Amilcar Cetino Perez said his last words, what appeared
to be a prayer. Cetino and Tomas Cerrate Hernandez were members of a notorious
kidnap gang believed to be responsible for death threats against the family of
President Alfonso Portillo, prompting Portillo to send some relatives to Canada.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Fall
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks slipped Friday as investors were discouraged by
overnight falls in stocks. The Nikkei shed 105.78 points, to 17,370.12 points in
early trading. In New York, the Dow Jones industrial average fell 129.75 to
close at 10,398.04. The Nasdaq composite index was down 63.11 at 3,877.23.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Rocker, Braves Defeat Mets 6-4
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- John Rocker pitched a perfect eighth inning tonight night as
the Atlanta Braves beat New York 6-4, ending the Mets' seven-game winning
streak. With police packed all over the park, the crowd of 46,998 jeered as
Rocker warmed up. The booing did not unnerve him, however. He struck out Robin
Ventura and retired Todd Zeile and Jay Payton on grounders. Andres Galarraga
homered, tripled and drove in four runs as Atlanta won the opener of a four-game
series for the NL East lead.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by RICHARD A. SOMMA
</SUBHEAD>
