<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 23:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Leone Rebels Release 21 Captives  </HEADLINE>
By JONATHAN PAYE-LAYLEH
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONROVIA, Liberia (AP) -- Smiling broadly, 21 U.N. peacekeepers
arrived Thursday in the Liberian capital after being held for weeks
at a rebel base in neighboring Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
   The country's feared Revolutionary United Front rebels handed
over the Indian captives late Wednesday to Liberian authorities in
the remote border town of Foya, officials said. They were
transported to Monrovia Thursday by a government-chartered
helicopter and expected to arrive back in Sierra Leone on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   More than 200 U.N. troops from India remained surrounded,
however, in a U.N. compound in the rebel stronghold of Kailahun,
about 200 miles east of the Sierra Leonean capital, Freetown. Their
fate, along with 11 unarmed military observers trapped in Kailahun
was still unclear.
</P>
<P>
   Mulbah said Liberia ''wants the fighting to stop'' to allow
their safe passage from the area.
</P>
<P>
   The released captives, who had been held in the nearby town of
Pendembu since early June, were ''unconditionally released,''
according to Liberian Information Minister Joe Mulbah.
</P>
<P>
   The troops said they had been well treated by their captors.
</P>
<P>
   ''We had a good relationship with the RUF, no problem
whatsoever,'' said Lt. Col. Amit Sharma, as he drank bottles of
Coca-Cola at the Indian consulate in Monrovia.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan welcomed the move by rebels
and hoped the move would be followed by ''immediate and
unconditional freedom of movement'' for the besieged troops, said
deputy U.N. spokesman Manoel de Almeida e Silva in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The Security Council on Thursday neared agreement on a
resolution that would impose an embargo on the sale of Sierra Leone
diamonds and tighten the 1998 arms embargo for at least 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   The release of the peacekeepers was negotiated by a team
appointed by Liberian President Charles Taylor, the rebels' closest
regional ally during Sierra Leone's eight-year civil war, which was
supposed to have ended with the signing of a peace accord last
July.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor also helped negotiate the release last month of 500 U.N.
peacekeepers seized as rebels resumed fighting in early May. Unlike
the earlier hostages, which were released after being held for
three weeks, the 200 besieged peacekeepers have been allowed to
keep their weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Although an alliance of pro-government forces has managed to
push rebels away from the capital in recent weeks, government
soldiers and their allies from a former junta turned their guns on
each other Wednesday in the strategic town of Masiaka, about 45
miles east of the Freetown.
</P>
<P>
   Six government and 15 junta soldiers were killed in the
exchange, Sierra Leone military officials said Thursday, speaking
on condition of anonymity. It was not immediately clear what
prompted the clash between the uneasy allies who fought on opposing
sides during the war.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. peacekeepers were sent to restore order in Masiaka after
the shooting, U.N. military spokesman Lt. Cmdr. Patrick Coker said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Sierra Leonean government and its backers, including
Britain, accuse Taylor of using his position as mediator to protect
Liberia's alleged economic stake in the rebels' diamond mining
activities in eastern Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
   Liberia has also been accused of sending weapons and mercenaries
to aid the rebels, but vehemently denies the claims.
</P>
<P>
   The RUF rebels killed tens of thousands of civilians and
systematically maimed many more in a campaign of terror.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-29-00 2302 </TRAILER>
