<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopia-Eritrea Talks Move to D.C.  </HEADLINE>
By ANDREW ENGLAND
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) -- Indirect talks between Ethiopia and
Eritrea aimed at finding a permanent peace between the warring
neighbors will take place in Washington, officials said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Ethiopia and Eritrea said they have sent technical teams to the
United States to discuss demarcation of their disputed 620-mile
border, compensation for deportees and the origins of their 2-year
war.
</P>
<P>
   Under the mediation of the Organization of African Unity, the
two impoverished nations agreed June 18 to cease hostilities in a
conflict that has claimed the lives of tens of thousands on both
sides. U.S. special envoy Anthony Lake helped broker the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   However, many issues were left unresolved, and the accord fell
short of a full, unconditional cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
   There have been no reports of fighting since. But Ethiopia says
it will not withdraw its forces from parts of Eritrea they occupy
until U.N. peacekeepers are deployed in a buffer zone 15 miles
inside Eritrean territory as agreed to under the OAU accord. This
could take months, according to diplomats involved in the process.
</P>
<P>
   Since Eritrea gained independence from Ethiopia in 1993, their
common border has never been formally settled.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, State Department spokesman Philip Reeker said the
talks will start on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Ethiopian spokeswoman Selome Taddesse and Eritrean presidential
spokesman Yemane Gebremeskel told The Associated Press by telephone
that their delegations, made up of legal and technical experts,
would arrive in the United States on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In Geneva on Thursday, the United Nations called for more
control over the flow of arms to the Horn of Africa, highlighting
donors' fears that relief aid could be diverted to war efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ''The possibility of the diversion of funds from relief and
development programs, aiming to alleviate poverty, to war efforts
remains a recurrent concern,'' said a statement from the U.N. task
force responsible for developing a strategy to protect the region
from the effects of recurrent drought and feeding problems.
</P>
<P>
   Ethiopia and Eritrea are heavily reliant on international
assistance to help feed millions of drought victims.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
