<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 23:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Murder-Suicide at Wash. Hospital  </HEADLINE>
By LAURENCE M. CRUZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) -- Colleagues of a University of Washington medical
resident who killed himself after fatally shooting his supervisor
locked their doors when the man was around, a faculty member said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But his supervisor, Dr. Rodger Haggitt, apparently did not share
their fears. His door was unlocked Wednesday when Dr. Jian Chen
walked in for a meeting and shot Haggitt, 57, four times in the
torso before shooting himself in the head, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Staff and other medical residents at the university's medical
center said they started seeing signs of trouble months ago, when
faculty members told Chen his residency contract -- normally four to
five years -- would not be renewed for the 2001 academic year. It
was to expire Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Chen, a 42-year-old United States citizen originally from China,
apparently became upset when told he wouldn't be asked to return
because of English language problems and academic shortcomings,
both of which became apparent soon after he joined the program last
August, faculty members said at a news conference Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   When Chen showed no improvement, his workload was cut and he was
offered extra language classes, but it was not clear if he took
them, said Dr. Nelson Fausto, chairman of the department of
pathology, which Haggitt directed.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, faculty encouraged Chen to try another
residency program.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was somewhat self-destructive at the end. He wasn't taking
any initiative to get into another program,'' said Dr. Edward Kim,
another pathology resident.
</P>
<P>
   In May, fellow residents became concerned about Chen when they
found a phone book open to gun-shop listings and a map on his
computer showing the shop where Chen later bought the weapon,
campus police Capt. Randy Stegmeier said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The fear was not so much that he was going to hurt somebody
else but that he was going to hurt himself,'' Fausto said.
</P>
<P>
   In a meeting May 23 with campus police and faculty, Chen
reportedly said he wanted the weapon for protection, said Dr. John
Gienapp, director of graduate medical education program assessment
and development. Others there urged him to get counseling, but he
said ''he had no psychological problems that needed to be
treated,'' Gienapp said.
</P>
<P>
   The King County Medical Examiner's Office listed Haggitt 's
death as homicide and Chen's as suicide. Stegmeier said: ''It's
possible that ... Dr. Chen became angrier (during the meeting) and
decided to take Dr. Haggitt's life, or Dr. Haggitt may have tried
to intercede to stop him taking his own life.''
</P>
<P>
   One of several undated letters found in Chen's backpack at the
scene indicated Chen ''did intend to take his own life but did not
intend to take Dr. Haggitt's life,'' Stegmeier said.
</P>
<P>
   Haggitt, 57, a doctor of anatomic pathology, joined the
university in 1984 as director of the division of hospital
pathology. He earned his medical degree from the University of
Tennessee in 1967 and completed training in pathology at Baptist
Memorial Hospital in Memphis and New England Deaconess Hospital in
Boston. He was married with three adult children.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-29-00 2308 </TRAILER>
