<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 23:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Democrats spar over women delegates for national convention  </HEADLINE>
By DAVE COLLINS
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - State Democrats are bickering over the
appointments of three women as delegates to the Democratic National
Convention, a dispute triggered by the national party's push to
send equal numbers of men and women to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats' dispute resolution committee on Thursday night
dismissed a complaint by a state delegate to the national
convention for former presidential candidate Bill Bradley, said
Democratic State Chairman Edward Marcus.
</P>
<P>
   The complainant, Audrey Blondin, a Torrington lawyer, said she
submitted a written statement because she was unable to attend the
hearing. A copy of the statement was unavailable Thursday night.
Blondin said it was in her office.
</P>
<P>
   ''The process raised questions, that's what we said. The three
delegates were put in and stepped down,'' she said from her home
late Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Blondin said she was contacted by the Gore campaign and agreed
to file a complaint because ''my belief is they make rules and
regulations for a reason and they should be followed. It doesn't
make a lot of sense to have a set of procedures drafted and then
not follow them.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the complaint must be forwarded to two separate national
committees for final resolution. Marcus said a decision should be
made within five to seven days.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our hope is that based on the evidence that was elicited at
the hearing, the rules committee and the credentials committee will
dismiss the charges and certify the delegation,'' Marcus said.
</P>
<P>
   The squabble started last month, when the Democratic National
Committee told the state party that it didn't have enough women
delegates to the national convention in August. The Connecticut men
outnumbered the women 37-30.
</P>
<P>
   The national party requires that delegates from each state be
equally divided among men and women.
</P>
<P>
   So three male Connecticut delegates - Bridgeport Mayor Joseph
Ganim, former state comptroller William Curry and Stratford
Democratic town chairman Dick Miron - resigned to make room for
three women.
</P>
<P>
   It is the appointment of those three women that was being
challenged Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Marcus said that he conferred with Vice President Al Gore's
Connecticut presidential campaign coordinator and appointed Ganim's
wife, Jennifer; Curry's sister, Kathleen; and Miron's ex-wife,
Anne.
</P>
<P>
   The appointments surprised 26 party members, who signed a
petition challenging the three new delegates. The petition, which
calls party leaders' actions ''blatant'' violations of party rules,
was the basis for Thursday night's hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Blondin said members of Gore's campaign staff asked her to
challenge the appointments of the three women delegates. She said
Marcus broke the rules when appointing them.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was concerned enough to not have any problem getting
involved in the process,'' Blondin, a Litchfield selectwoman, said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's our training as attorneys to be creative and advocate
zealously on our clients' behalf,'' she said. ''But that doesn't
mean we break the rules and use the process in a way it was not
meant to be used.''
</P>
<P>
   Blondin declined to say which Gore staff members asked her to
challenge the delegates.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore's Connecticut campaign coordinator, Marilyn Cohen of
West Hartford, said she was a principal decision-maker in approving
the three women delegates.
</P>
<P>
   ''It comes as a surprise to me that I am alleged to have had no
involvement,'' Cohen wrote in a June 12 letter to Marcus.
</P>
<P>
   She said party rules allow the state party chairman and the
state's presidential campaign coordinator to appoint new delegates
to replace delegates who resign.
</P>
<P>
   Democrat Martin Dunleavy, a former New Haven alderman, has said
that the Democratic National Committee asked him to initiate a
challenge to the three women delegates.	   Marcus said Thursday that Dunleavy is
upset over not getting a
delegate's position.
</P>
<P>
   ''They are good Democrats,'' Marcus said about the delegates in
question. ''Everything was done by and according to the rules.''
</P>
<P>
   After the state party's dispute resolution committee decides the
issue, the matter will then go to the party's rules and credentials
committees, Marcus said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-29-00 2312 </TRAILER>
