<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 23:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Takes War Crimes Exemption Step  </HEADLINE>
By EDITH M. LEDERER
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The United States said Thursday it has
negotiated a key first step toward an exemption for U.S. citizens
from prosecution by the world's first permanent war crimes
tribunal.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Ambassador David Scheffer, the ambassador-at-large for war
crimes issues, said he is hoping to win final agreement from more
than 100 countries when the commission preparing for the court's
operation holds its next meeting in November.
</P>
<P>
   ''We know the larger part of our proposal is awaiting debate in
November and December,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Dicker, associate counsel of Human Rights Watch, said
the vast majority of countries oppose a U.S. exemption and ''if the
U.S. government thinks otherwise, they have a big surprise coming
in November.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, as the commission's current three-week meeting
neared its Friday deadline, Scheffer was optimistic that the first
hurdle had been crossed and the gateway had been opened for an
exemption, which the United States views as a major national
security issue.
</P>
<P>
   The United States was one of seven countries voting ''no'' when
120 countries approved the treaty to establish the International
Criminal Court in July 1998 in Rome.
</P>
<P>
   Under the treaty, the court will step in only when countries are
unwilling or unable to dispense justice. It can act when either the
country where the crime took place, or the country whose nationals
committed the crime, have ratified the statute.
</P>
<P>
   What the United States objects to is that American citizens can
be subject to the court's jurisdiction if an alleged crime is
committed in a country that had ratified the treaty -- even if the
United States is not a party. Washington says this would leave U.S.
troops and citizens vulnerable to politically motivated
prosecutions.
</P>
<P>
   Pressure on the Clinton administration intensified when Sen.
Jesse Helms, a North Carolina Republican, introduced legislation
earlier this month which would bar U.S. cooperation with the court,
as long as the United States has not ratified the treaty creating
it.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is clearly a locomotive coming down on us,'' Scheffer said,
''but I would hope the locomotive stops because it's recognized
that we are making progress in these negotiations to achieve the
very objective that is behind this legislation.''
</P>
<P>
   Scheffer expressed satisfaction that a rule agreed to by
delegates on Thursday would provide ''a gateway'' for the United
States in November to seek an exemption for the surrender of U.S.
citizens through an agreement with the court.
</P>
<P>
   The rule deals with conditions under which the court may procede
with a request for the surrender of a suspect.
</P>
<P>
   In the U.S. view, Scheffer said, the rule does not preclude the
court from entering a separate international agreement with a
country on the surrender of suspects.
</P>
<P>
   But Richard Dicker, associate counsel of Human Rights Watch,
said ''to interpret this rule as authorizing the court to enter
into international agreements without an amendment to the treaty is
wishful thinking.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-29-00 2333 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000629.0205 </DOCNO>
